I'm sorry, I've got a heck
of a lot to get done today.

33
00:03:47.072 --> 00:03:51.168
And you know what they say.
"The early bird catches the worm".

34
00:03:51.268 --> 00:03:55.064
Well, if you do this again,
one more time, I'm calling the cops.

35
00:03:57.062 --> 00:03:58.959
And how about
mowing your lawns?

36
00:03:58.960 --> 00:04:01.158
It's a bloody disgrace
to the neighbourhood.

37
00:04:06.852 --> 00:04:07.951
Yeah, alright.

38
00:04:14.545 --> 00:04:15.744
Hi, kid.

39
00:04:32.627 --> 00:04:34.325
Here we are, the...

40
00:04:35.324 --> 00:04:36.822
perfect recipe...

41
00:04:38.021 --> 00:04:39.620
two of Chevy...

42
00:04:40.818 --> 00:04:42.017
one of Ford.

43
00:04:46.113 --> 00:04:50.109
I think those '36 Chevy pistons...

44
00:04:50.409 --> 00:04:52.906
must have a touch of titanium
or something in them.

45
00:04:52.907 --> 00:04:54.804
They come up real good,
you know.

46
00:04:55.903 --> 00:04:57.502
Hey the kettle's boiling.

47
00:04:57.702 --> 00:04:59.700
Make yourself useful,
make some tea.

48
00:05:05.394 --> 00:05:07.392
Can we have a biscuit too?

49
00:05:07.891 --> 00:05:10.389
- What?
- Can I have a gingernut?

50
00:05:10.589 --> 00:05:12.786
Yeah, you know where they are,
help yourself.

51
00:05:17.482 --> 00:05:19.180
Now you stay over there,
stay there.

52
00:05:28.970 --> 00:05:31.668
- Right.
- What are you doing for Christmas, Burt?

53
00:05:31.867 --> 00:05:33.765
Christmas? I don't know.
Why?

54
00:05:33.965 --> 00:05:36.062
Are you angling
for a present or something?

55
00:05:36.063 --> 00:05:39.160
- No, I wondered if you were going away.
- No...

56
00:05:39.460 --> 00:05:43.056
no time for Christmas, lad.
Got a lot of work to do.

57
00:05:43.356 --> 00:05:46.453
I only managed twenty seven
test runs this year.

58
00:05:46.553 --> 00:05:49.550
You know, twenty four on the beach
and three on the road.

59
00:05:49.849 --> 00:05:51.448
All illegal like.

60
00:05:53.246 --> 00:05:55.743
I was going a bit over the speed limit,
I'll have to admit.

61
00:05:55.943 --> 00:05:58.441
- How fast were you going?
- I don't know, I haven't a clue.

62
00:05:58.641 --> 00:06:01.438
That's why I have to get up
to Bonneville.

63
00:06:02.537 --> 00:06:04.435
Found out how fast she will go.

64
00:06:20.519 --> 00:06:21.817
Now, there you go.

65
00:06:22.417 --> 00:06:24.515
Got to get the piston out
of the mould...

66
00:06:25.514 --> 00:06:26.712
and Bob's your uncle.

67
00:06:27.612 --> 00:06:29.410
Right, this is...

68
00:06:30.009 --> 00:06:32.407
the last part
of the operation now.

69
00:06:32.607 --> 00:06:33.905
To chill the metal.

70
00:06:34.405 --> 00:06:37.202
It heat treats it.
Right, watch yourself.

71
00:06:40.698 --> 00:06:43.196
That's where I got the water
for the kettle from.

72
00:06:43.496 --> 00:06:48.291
Well, you know, it gives the tea
a nice tang of titanium, doesn't it?

73
00:06:48.690 --> 00:06:50.488
Now this bloke,
he once asked me...

74
00:06:50.489 --> 00:06:54.585
"How do you heat treat your pistons?"
And I said: "I don't, mate"...

75
00:06:54.585 --> 00:06:58.680
I just, you know, bung them
in cold water and Bob's your uncle".

76
00:06:58.780 --> 00:07:01.577
And he said:
"Well, that's the heat treatment"...

77
00:07:01.578 --> 00:07:05.673
and he just laughed and
shook his head and walked away like.

78
00:07:05.973 --> 00:07:08.570
Well, look this could be
the perfect piston.

79
00:07:08.571 --> 00:07:11.368
It blooming well ought to be,
I've made hundreds of them.

80
00:07:11.568 --> 00:07:15.064
Look at them all up there,
all blown to smithereens.

81
00:07:16.163 --> 00:07:19.460
- You made all those?
- Yeah, I did. Look perfect.

82
00:07:19.959 --> 00:07:21.857
Beautiful, no inclusions see?

83
00:07:22.357 --> 00:07:27.651
Now Tommy, does your mother have
a carving knife I could borrow?

84
00:07:27.652 --> 00:07:28.950
Carving knife? Yeah?

85
00:07:29.250 --> 00:07:30.948
Yeah.
I need a good sharp knife.

86
00:07:39.440 --> 00:07:40.738
Hang on.

87
00:07:41.138 --> 00:07:43.735
- Thomas, what are you up to?
- Nothing, Mum.

88
00:07:44.035 --> 00:07:45.233
Can I have some bread
and peanut butter?

89
00:07:45.234 --> 00:07:48.031
Ok, but make sure you put everything
away when you've finished.

90
00:07:49.230 --> 00:07:50.529
Sorry about that.

91
00:07:59.619 --> 00:08:00.618
Tom.

92
00:08:01.418 --> 00:08:04.215
- Don't forget the wood.
- No, Mum.

93
00:08:09.010 --> 00:08:10.109
Right.

94
00:08:11.508 --> 00:08:13.306
I hope to get as much...

95
00:08:13.705 --> 00:08:15.903
rubber off as possible.

96
00:08:16.403 --> 00:08:18.900
It has to be perfectly bald,
like that, you see.

97
00:08:19.400 --> 00:08:22.896
- Why's that?
- Well, at high speed...

98
00:08:23.196 --> 00:08:25.394
the centrifugal force...

99
00:08:25.793 --> 00:08:27.891
expands the tyre and...

100
00:08:28.590 --> 00:08:31.987
it rubs against
the frame of the bike.

101
00:08:32.786 --> 00:08:35.883
Have to be careful not to cut
through the cords though.

102
00:08:38.081 --> 00:08:40.778
- Why do you pee on your lemon tree?
- What?

103
00:08:40.978 --> 00:08:43.376
Why do you pee on your
lemon tree?

104
00:08:46.373 --> 00:08:48.770
- Who says I do that?
- Mum says she sees you...

105
00:08:48.870 --> 00:08:51.268
every morning and
she goes on and on about it.

106
00:08:51.567 --> 00:08:52.766
Does she?

107
00:08:54.564 --> 00:08:58.860
Well, it's good for it. You shouldn't
waste anything in this world, sonny.

108
00:08:59.959 --> 00:09:02.257
- Well, I'd better be off home.
- Alright then.

109
00:09:02.457 --> 00:09:04.654
Mum gets a bit cross if
I stay over here too long.

110
00:09:04.954 --> 00:09:05.853
She does.

111
00:09:08.051 --> 00:09:12.447
- Are you finished with the knife?
- Not yet, I'll drop it by later.

112
00:09:12.646 --> 00:09:15.743
No, don't do that,
I'll pick it up after school tomorrow.

113
00:09:16.043 --> 00:09:17.242
Alright.

114
00:09:18.540 --> 00:09:20.439
- Bye.
- Cheerio.

115
00:09:29.529 --> 00:09:31.227
- Burt Munro.
- Yeah.

116
00:09:31.228 --> 00:09:33.525
I believe you have
my carving knife.

117
00:09:33.825 --> 00:09:35.823
- Oh yes.
- And my sharpener.

118
00:09:38.021 --> 00:09:39.719
Hang on, here we are.

119
00:09:43.316 --> 00:09:44.614
Well, thanks a lot, love.

120
00:09:54.804 --> 00:09:56.203
G'day Frank. How are you?

121
00:09:56.303 --> 00:09:59.000
Oh not bad, could be better,
could be worse.

122
00:09:59.100 --> 00:10:02.097
I see your front tyre's going
a bit flat on you there, Burt.

123
00:10:02.397 --> 00:10:05.693
Yeah, well, the good news is,
it's only flat on the bottom.

124
00:10:06.093 --> 00:10:08.990
I'll see you tomorrow night
for the fun and games.

125
00:10:08.991 --> 00:10:09.989
It'll be a good one.

126
00:10:12.287 --> 00:10:13.386
Hello, Fran.

127
00:10:14.684 --> 00:10:18.580
- Give us the lot will you? The usual.
- One pension check. Coming up.

128
00:10:19.979 --> 00:10:21.378
Fran...

129
00:10:21.977 --> 00:10:25.473
I want to ask you a question,
the answer to which is...

130
00:10:27.072 --> 00:10:28.271
a definite yes.

131
00:10:28.870 --> 00:10:30.968
- Alright, Fran?
- Alright.

132
00:10:31.667 --> 00:10:32.766
Yes.

133
00:10:33.765 --> 00:10:35.064
What is the question, Burt?

134
00:10:35.563 --> 00:10:38.660
Would you feel inclined to,
you know, accompany...

135
00:10:39.659 --> 00:10:43.455
an impeccable young gentleman
to a local do tomorrow night?

136
00:10:45.354 --> 00:10:47.651
You're asking me on a date,
Burt Munro?

137
00:10:48.650 --> 00:10:51.048
Well, yeah, I suppose
I am actually, aren't I?

138
00:10:52.446 --> 00:10:53.945
- Would you?
- You're on.

139
00:11:01.138 --> 00:11:02.836
- Hello, son.
- Hey, Burt.

140
00:11:03.935 --> 00:11:05.334
That's disgusting.

141
00:11:06.233 --> 00:11:07.731
It is, isn't it?

142
00:11:08.430 --> 00:11:11.627
All dressed up
for the do tonight...

143
00:11:11.727 --> 00:11:13.524
and I couldn't get
my best shoes on...

144
00:11:13.525 --> 00:11:16.123
because my toe nails had grown
like oyster shells.

145
00:11:16.822 --> 00:11:18.121
Alright...

146
00:11:18.520 --> 00:11:20.019
this should do the trick.

147
00:11:21.517 --> 00:11:22.816
There, look at that.

148
00:11:23.116 --> 00:11:24.414
Little twinkle toes.

149
00:11:31.407 --> 00:11:33.306
- Thanks, Burt.
- Right on.

150
00:11:42.796 --> 00:11:44.594
- Evening, Burt.
- Thank you...

151
00:11:44.894 --> 00:11:47.092
- this is Fran.
- Hello, Fran.

152
00:11:47.391 --> 00:11:48.790
Thank you very much.

153
00:11:48.990 --> 00:11:50.988
- Hello, Duncan.
- Burt.

154
00:11:51.687 --> 00:11:55.683
Just going to say hello and be back
in a second, love, alright?

155
00:11:56.882 --> 00:11:58.980
- How are you?
- Bike going well?

156
00:11:59.180 --> 00:12:00.378
Yeah, not too bad.

157
00:12:00.778 --> 00:12:02.976
- Happy birthday, Burt.
- Thanks a lot, mate.

158
00:12:03.276 --> 00:12:05.274
This is a bit of
a surprise, isn't it?

159
00:12:06.073 --> 00:12:08.569
Would you like to buy
a raffle ticket or two?

160
00:12:08.570 --> 00:12:11.567
- What's it for?
- Porky the Pig plus two dozen beers.

161
00:12:11.767 --> 00:12:15.463
We're raising money to send
Burt to the USA. Our mate, Burt.

162
00:12:17.561 --> 00:12:19.559
Hello. Come on and dance.

163
00:12:21.058 --> 00:12:24.354
- What's this? The twist?
- This is the twist. You know the twist?

164
00:12:24.954 --> 00:12:26.552
Come twist with me.

165
00:12:29.250 --> 00:12:30.748
See you can twist.

166
00:12:33.945 --> 00:12:36.642
<i>- That's it, that's it.
- This must be it, the atomic invasion.</i>

167
00:12:37.242 --> 00:12:40.338
Then the air clears
and the dust settles down.

168
00:12:40.438 --> 00:12:43.136
You look outside,
have they levelled the town?

169
00:12:43.735 --> 00:12:45.933
But there, in the yard...

170
00:12:45.934 --> 00:12:47.831
so briskly alive...

171
00:12:48.031 --> 00:12:50.229
stands Burt Munro's trusty...

172
00:12:50.628 --> 00:12:52.726
old Indian Scout '45.

173
00:12:58.021 --> 00:13:00.318
That was a wonderful
tribute to Burt.

174
00:13:00.618 --> 00:13:03.415
Now come on Burt, we want you up
on stage, come on...

175
00:13:03.715 --> 00:13:05.114
come on, up you come.

176
00:13:08.810 --> 00:13:12.107
I hope all of you have bought
a raffle ticket tonight...

177
00:13:12.406 --> 00:13:16.602
because we believe Burt will put
the Southland Motorcycle Club...

178
00:13:16.603 --> 00:13:17.701
<i>on the map.</i>

179
00:13:28.390 --> 00:13:29.989
What's going on out there?

180
00:13:30.588 --> 00:13:31.987
Get out of here.

181
00:13:33.985 --> 00:13:34.984
Oh, dear.

182
00:13:42.576 --> 00:13:46.872
Well folks, it looks like
I've cracked it, I've um you know.

183
00:13:47.072 --> 00:13:48.770
You Burt Munro?

184
00:13:49.469 --> 00:13:51.168
- What did he say?
- I said, are you Burt Munro?

185
00:13:51.867 --> 00:13:53.965
Are you looking for old Burt?

186
00:13:54.264 --> 00:13:56.262
I don't know,
anyone seen Burt anywhere?

187
00:13:56.662 --> 00:13:58.260
Anyone seen Burt?

188
00:13:58.660 --> 00:14:00.558
- No, he's...
- You are, you're Burt Munro.

189
00:14:01.158 --> 00:14:03.755
You're the old codger,
rides the Army Indian right?

190
00:14:03.955 --> 00:14:06.252
That old joker.
Burt Munro. Yeah.

191
00:14:06.952 --> 00:14:08.450
Yeah, that's me I think.

192
00:14:09.449 --> 00:14:13.445
Now the, ah, young fella,
the army Indian is a real dog...

193
00:14:13.745 --> 00:14:15.643
what I've got is the...

194
00:14:16.143 --> 00:14:20.238
genuine article,
the 1920 V twin Scout.

195
00:14:20.538 --> 00:14:23.835
<i>- That's the one with the pedals, right?
- Don't put up with that, Burt.</i>

196
00:14:25.333 --> 00:14:30.328
No, well. Well, I don't know what sort of
push bikes you monkeys came into town on...

197
00:14:30.428 --> 00:14:35.223
but I know my old timer would trash
the backsides of whatever they are.

198
00:14:35.923 --> 00:14:38.021
- I don't think so, granddad.
- No.

199
00:14:39.120 --> 00:14:43.116
Well, why don't you chaps
put your money where your mouth is?

200
00:14:44.115 --> 00:14:45.813
You're on. You old coot.

201
00:14:49.609 --> 00:14:52.007
- Looks like they've chickened out, Burt.
- What?

202
00:14:52.008 --> 00:14:54.404
- Looks like they've chickened out.
- They're here.

203
00:14:55.903 --> 00:14:57.002
They're here.

204
00:15:01.197 --> 00:15:02.796
That's nice of them
to show up isn't it?

205
00:15:10.788 --> 00:15:13.685
A hundred says
the Indian comes last.

206
00:15:13.985 --> 00:15:15.183
Right.

207
00:15:37.761 --> 00:15:38.960
Come on, Burt.

208
00:15:41.357 --> 00:15:42.556
Ready, steady...

209
00:15:44.154 --> 00:15:45.153
go.

210
00:15:49.649 --> 00:15:51.347
Come on, give me a push.

211
00:15:53.145 --> 00:15:54.844
- Come on.
- Come on, Burt.

212
00:15:55.044 --> 00:15:57.541
Give me a push.
Come on, push hard.

213
00:16:00.138 --> 00:16:01.237
Bugger it.

214
00:16:04.035 --> 00:16:05.034
Bugger it.

215
00:16:06.732 --> 00:16:08.130
Come on! Go!

216
00:16:52.186 --> 00:16:53.185
Bugger!

217
00:16:53.485 --> 00:16:55.083
Nice bike, granddad.

218
00:16:55.583 --> 00:16:56.682
Loser.

219
00:17:15.063 --> 00:17:16.262
Thanks, fellas.

220
00:17:16.362 --> 00:17:18.860
- Better luck next time.
- Better luck, Burt.

221
00:17:24.254 --> 00:17:25.253
There you go.

222
00:17:25.653 --> 00:17:27.451
- Well, thanks, love.
- Careful, it's hot.

223
00:17:29.749 --> 00:17:32.746
Well, at least I gave them
a good run for their money.

224
00:17:33.245 --> 00:17:34.844
On the downward leg anyway.

225
00:17:35.943 --> 00:17:39.439
Burt... What's it going to cost
to get over to America?

226
00:17:39.440 --> 00:17:40.937
Sorry, love.
What did you say?

227
00:17:40.938 --> 00:17:42.936
How much is it gonna cost
to get over to America?

228
00:17:43.735 --> 00:17:46.732
I don't know,
about two thousand I'm told.

229
00:17:47.231 --> 00:17:49.329
And how much money
have you got now?

230
00:17:50.728 --> 00:17:55.223
Apart from today's disaster and
the dough from last night and...

231
00:17:55.224 --> 00:17:58.320
the pension money
I've been saving...

232
00:17:58.620 --> 00:18:03.515
...about twelve hundred and 75 dollars,
United States dollars, I reckon.

233
00:18:04.414 --> 00:18:06.312
Well, I could lend you some money.

234
00:18:06.512 --> 00:18:11.407
That's very kind of you Fran love, but no.
I couldn't do that love. No, thanks.

235
00:18:11.607 --> 00:18:13.805
Well, there must be
something you can do.

236
00:18:14.404 --> 00:18:17.201
Well, I haven't told anyone
else this, Fran, but...

237
00:18:17.401 --> 00:18:22.096
I don't reckon I'll be going to Bonneville.
I mean not this year anyway and...

238
00:18:22.796 --> 00:18:26.592
you know, seven hundred dollars
is a lot of money to find...

239
00:18:26.892 --> 00:18:31.087
and the boat leaves in five days.

240
00:18:33.185 --> 00:18:37.681
Except I would like to see
how fast she would really go...

241
00:18:37.781 --> 00:18:42.975
before I fall off the perch as it were.
Before I ah, kicked the old bucket.

242
00:18:53.365 --> 00:18:54.864
Hello, Lloyd.

243
00:18:55.263 --> 00:18:56.562
Gidday, Burt.

244
00:18:56.762 --> 00:18:57.761
Shame about the fall.

245
00:18:58.060 --> 00:18:59.859
Well, I'm still
in one piece aren't I?

246
00:19:00.858 --> 00:19:02.355
What are you having tonight?

247
00:19:02.356 --> 00:19:04.754
Specialty of the house,
pea, pie and pud.

248
00:19:04.953 --> 00:19:06.552
- That's five bob.
- Alright.

249
00:19:06.951 --> 00:19:10.448
Burt? Why don't you take out
a mortgage on your house?

250
00:19:10.648 --> 00:19:12.446
- What house?
- Well, your property.

251
00:19:12.546 --> 00:19:14.444
I mean it's worth something.

252
00:19:16.442 --> 00:19:17.640
Here you are.

253
00:19:17.641 --> 00:19:19.938
Burt Munro,
look at the colour of your hands.

254
00:19:20.038 --> 00:19:22.636
- What's the matter with them.
- You're gonna wash those mitts...

255
00:19:22.637 --> 00:19:24.434
before you put them
anywhere near me.

256
00:19:24.734 --> 00:19:26.032
There we are.

257
00:19:59.799 --> 00:20:00.897
Wakee, wakee.

258
00:20:01.697 --> 00:20:03.195
Time to rise...

259
00:20:04.194 --> 00:20:05.693
and shine.

260
00:20:07.191 --> 00:20:09.089
Burt, you're a sweetie.

261
00:20:09.888 --> 00:20:12.686
Got to get out of here before
the neighbours spot me.

262
00:20:18.280 --> 00:20:20.977
Burt, this tastes a bit odd.

263
00:20:22.176 --> 00:20:23.175
Metallic!

264
00:20:24.574 --> 00:20:28.370
<i>You are my sunshine
My only sunshine</i>

265
00:20:28.570 --> 00:20:29.669
Oh, crikey!

266
00:20:30.168 --> 00:20:31.367
What?

267
00:20:31.667 --> 00:20:33.065
I've got a pain in my chest.

268
00:20:34.564 --> 00:20:36.362
He's in the shed, hurry.

269
00:20:40.857 --> 00:20:43.355
Mum, Dad,
something's happened to Burt.

270
00:20:51.047 --> 00:20:52.646
Burt, what's wrong with you?

271
00:20:52.845 --> 00:20:55.143
I'll be alright Tommy,
don't worry about me.

272
00:20:55.743 --> 00:20:57.541
- Are you sure?
- Yeah.

273
00:21:19.219 --> 00:21:22.815
What are you all staring at?
Dirty old men need love too.

274
00:21:27.211 --> 00:21:28.909
- Mr. Munro.
- Hello.

275
00:21:29.109 --> 00:21:31.607
So, what's the story, Doc?

276
00:21:31.906 --> 00:21:36.002
- I'm sorry, it's not good news.
- Oh, yeah. Well, fire away.

277
00:21:37.601 --> 00:21:39.399
You've had an attack of angina.

278
00:21:40.598 --> 00:21:42.396
You have arterial sclerosis.

279
00:21:43.195 --> 00:21:44.494
And what's that?

280
00:21:44.793 --> 00:21:47.391
It's a narrowing
of the arteries from the heart.

281
00:21:47.591 --> 00:21:48.590
Oh, dear.

282
00:21:48.889 --> 00:21:51.087
Yeah, I'm afraid there's not too much
we can do for you at your age...

283
00:21:51.187 --> 00:21:53.285
other than suggesting you
take it easy.

284
00:21:54.484 --> 00:21:57.681
Look if you have another attack,
pop one of these under your tongue...

285
00:21:57.880 --> 00:22:00.078
let it dissolve
and then swallow the saliva.

286
00:22:00.178 --> 00:22:02.676
The pain should be gone
in thirty seconds.

287
00:22:02.875 --> 00:22:05.573
- Yeah, what do you call these things?
- Trinitrate pills.

288
00:22:06.372 --> 00:22:08.370
Um better known as nitro glycerine.

289
00:22:08.670 --> 00:22:12.066
- The stuff you blow things up with.
- Yes, but in much smaller quantities.

290
00:22:12.067 --> 00:22:13.065
Alright.

291
00:22:14.564 --> 00:22:18.060
Will this have any affect on
me riding my bike?

292
00:22:19.958 --> 00:22:23.455
Unfortunately, I think your
motorcycling days are over.

293
00:22:23.754 --> 00:22:24.753
Like hell they are.

294
00:22:39.439 --> 00:22:40.737
It won't be much longer.

295
00:22:49.229 --> 00:22:50.528
Springfield.

296
00:22:51.726 --> 00:22:55.523
Springfield.
That's where the Indians come from.

297
00:22:55.623 --> 00:22:58.220
- Indians?
- Yeah, the Indians...

298
00:22:59.019 --> 00:23:00.717
from Springfield,
Massachusetts.

299
00:23:01.916 --> 00:23:03.615
The world's greatest
motorcycle.

300
00:23:04.614 --> 00:23:06.312
- Is that so?
- That's right.

301
00:23:07.710 --> 00:23:10.108
- You can come through now.
- Alright, thank you.

302
00:23:11.007 --> 00:23:12.805
Yeah, Springfield.

303
00:23:14.903 --> 00:23:18.100
<i>The plan is for me
to drive up to Timaru and...</i>

304
00:23:18.400 --> 00:23:23.295
there me and my bike...
will catch a boat to the US of A to...

305
00:23:23.395 --> 00:23:26.791
Los Angeles,
and the boat leaves on Saturday.

306
00:23:26.991 --> 00:23:29.589
And I'll buy a car
in Los Angeles...

307
00:23:29.688 --> 00:23:32.286
and drive up to Utah,
to the Bonneville Salt Flats.

308
00:23:32.486 --> 00:23:35.782
- It's really important you do this trip?
- Sure is mate, you know.

309
00:23:36.681 --> 00:23:40.278
Ever since I was a lad I've been
interested in things that go fast...

310
00:23:40.478 --> 00:23:42.376
you know things
that roll and go and...

311
00:23:42.775 --> 00:23:46.072
at Bonneville things go real fast.
It's...

312
00:23:46.372 --> 00:23:49.668
this giant dried up lake bed...

313
00:23:49.868 --> 00:23:52.565
and it goes for miles
and miles and it's dead flat...

314
00:23:52.566 --> 00:23:56.562
and you can drive a vehicle just
as fast as it will go and it's...

315
00:23:56.861 --> 00:23:59.857
...one of the few places
on earth...

316
00:23:59.858 --> 00:24:04.054
where you can find out just what
your machine is capable of.

317
00:24:04.354 --> 00:24:08.849
In fact here I'm on the, that's me on the
front of the New Zealand Motorcyclist.

318
00:24:09.149 --> 00:24:10.448
That's the Indian there.

319
00:24:10.548 --> 00:24:12.645
- Very good!
- Yeah, a few years ago.

320
00:24:13.045 --> 00:24:14.642
So I'd best be off soon...

321
00:24:14.643 --> 00:24:17.241
because I don't know how much longer
I've got to live you see.

322
00:24:17.242 --> 00:24:19.637
Yes, I don't think
I heard that last statement.

323
00:24:19.638 --> 00:24:21.836
I said I don't know
how much longer I've got to live.

324
00:24:21.837 --> 00:24:23.435
I heard you the first time.

325
00:24:23.734 --> 00:24:25.433
So... tell me, Burt.

326
00:24:25.632 --> 00:24:28.530
What are you offering
as collateral for this loan?

327
00:24:28.629 --> 00:24:33.225
Well, my tools, my bits and pieces, my
trophies and a lot of things like this.

328
00:24:33.226 --> 00:24:36.322
Well, I don't think they'd be
of much interest to the bank...

329
00:24:36.323 --> 00:24:38.520
I think we'd be looking for
something more substantial.

330
00:24:38.520 --> 00:24:41.517
Something like the deed
of title to your property.

331
00:24:43.515 --> 00:24:47.211
- Did you get the money?
- Yep, I'm off on Thursday.

332
00:24:47.610 --> 00:24:50.508
Thursday? That soon?
I wish I could come too.

333
00:24:51.307 --> 00:24:52.605
Oh, maybe next time.

334
00:24:54.903 --> 00:24:57.900
Thomas. It's dinner time.
Come home now.

335
00:24:58.100 --> 00:25:01.197
- Nearly finished, Mrs. Jackson.
- Yeah, Mum, we're almost finished.

336
00:25:03.894 --> 00:25:05.393
See you after dinner, Burt.

337
00:25:06.192 --> 00:25:07.491
Alright, lad.

338
00:25:15.582 --> 00:25:17.281
Hey, not so fast.

339
00:25:17.481 --> 00:25:19.079
I'm the record breaker.

340
00:25:21.976 --> 00:25:23.275
Where are you going?

341
00:25:25.073 --> 00:25:26.771
And that's the...

342
00:25:27.271 --> 00:25:30.468
before I put the...
you know, the streamliner on it.

343
00:25:34.663 --> 00:25:35.662
What's that one?

344
00:25:36.462 --> 00:25:40.757
That's a girlfriend of mine
when I first bought the bike.

345
00:25:40.857 --> 00:25:42.456
It was a long time ago that was.

346
00:25:45.453 --> 00:25:48.450
Aren't you scared you'll kill
yourself if you crash?

347
00:25:48.749 --> 00:25:49.648
No...

348
00:25:49.948 --> 00:25:51.845
you...

349
00:25:51.846 --> 00:25:55.343
live more in five minutes
on a bike like this...

350
00:25:55.642 --> 00:25:58.240
going flat out than some people
live in a lifetime.

351
00:25:59.039 --> 00:26:00.736
And...

352
00:26:00.737 --> 00:26:04.933
yeah, more in five minutes.
That's my Dad there.

353
00:26:06.132 --> 00:26:07.630
And my mum.

354
00:26:09.129 --> 00:26:10.527
They're all gone.

355
00:26:12.725 --> 00:26:14.723
God, it's gone by so fast!

356
00:26:15.622 --> 00:26:18.519
You know,
danger is the spice of life...

357
00:26:18.719 --> 00:26:21.816
and you've got to take a risk every now
and again haven't you, son?

358
00:26:22.116 --> 00:26:25.213
You know that's
what makes life worthwhile.

359
00:26:26.312 --> 00:26:30.108
And you know,
having some nice ladies around...

360
00:26:30.408 --> 00:26:32.605
...can be a big help, mind you.

361
00:26:33.205 --> 00:26:36.501
- You really don't get scared?
- No, no.

362
00:26:38.100 --> 00:26:39.099
You know...

363
00:26:39.498 --> 00:26:42.196
when I was a boy
about your age...

364
00:26:42.495 --> 00:26:45.492
I had a little twin brother
whose name was Ernie...

365
00:26:45.692 --> 00:26:50.088
and one day our Dad was out
the back cutting down a tree...

366
00:26:50.887 --> 00:26:51.886
and...

367
00:26:52.685 --> 00:26:57.580
suddenly it got hung up, the tree
that is, it got stuck on something and...

368
00:26:58.579 --> 00:27:01.876
Ernie went to go and help.
All of a sudden the tree...

369
00:27:02.376 --> 00:27:06.372
slipped and fell on him
and killed him stone dead.

370
00:27:11.866 --> 00:27:13.764
I always remember that.

371
00:27:14.064 --> 00:27:18.959
Anyway, since then I've always tried
never to be scared of anything.

372
00:27:19.458 --> 00:27:20.856
Although I must say before...

373
00:27:20.857 --> 00:27:24.154
a big bike event I do
sometimes get nervous, you know...

374
00:27:25.852 --> 00:27:30.348
if the butterflies
in my stomach were cows...

375
00:27:30.647 --> 00:27:33.644
I'd be able to start
a dairy farm.

376
00:27:35.043 --> 00:27:36.441
That's funny.

377
00:27:37.540 --> 00:27:41.636
When they took you off in the ambulance
to the hospital. What happened?

378
00:27:41.936 --> 00:27:44.533
I don't know, just a touch
of indigestion I think.

379
00:27:44.933 --> 00:27:48.429
Yeah, that's all it was. There's nothing
wrong with me, don't you worry about me.

380
00:27:48.529 --> 00:27:50.228
And anyway at my age...

381
00:27:50.527 --> 00:27:54.124
any day above ground
and vertical is a good day.

382
00:27:54.723 --> 00:27:57.820
Listen, you take care
of this until I get back alright?

383
00:27:58.419 --> 00:28:02.316
- What happens if you don't come back?
- We'll talk about that then shan't we.

384
00:28:04.913 --> 00:28:06.410
- Hey, Burt?
- Yeah.

385
00:28:06.411 --> 00:28:08.310
Don't forget
to mow your lawns will you?

386
00:28:08.409 --> 00:28:10.607
- What?
- Don't forget to mow your lawns.

387
00:28:10.707 --> 00:28:12.505
My Dad goes on and on about it.

388
00:28:12.705 --> 00:28:13.804
He does, does he?

389
00:28:14.004 --> 00:28:17.101
He says it lowers the property
values of the neighbourhood.

390
00:28:18.599 --> 00:28:21.696
Well, oh dear,
we can't have that can we?

391
00:28:45.273 --> 00:28:46.272
What are you doing?

392
00:28:46.571 --> 00:28:48.869
Hello, son.
I'm just getting rid of the grass.

393
00:28:51.766 --> 00:28:54.463
Burt, what the hell
are you doing this time?

394
00:28:54.763 --> 00:28:57.860
Oh, like you said George
I'm getting rid of the grass...

395
00:28:58.359 --> 00:29:00.957
being a good neighbour
before I leave tomorrow.

396
00:29:01.257 --> 00:29:03.654
Tom, Tom!
Get back inside now!

397
00:29:04.453 --> 00:29:05.652
Now!

398
00:29:07.151 --> 00:29:08.449
Honestly, Burt!

399
00:29:12.645 --> 00:29:15.442
- What are they doing here?
- It might be the fire, Burt.

400
00:29:24.433 --> 00:29:26.331
Right, the tyre goes in first.

401
00:29:27.031 --> 00:29:28.329
That's it.

402
00:29:29.029 --> 00:29:31.326
That's it, Jeff. You've got it.

403
00:29:32.026 --> 00:29:33.524
This goes in here.

404
00:29:35.322 --> 00:29:36.621
Pills...

405
00:29:37.420 --> 00:29:38.819
license, passport.

406
00:29:39.818 --> 00:29:42.315
Right, let's see,
I've got everything?

407
00:29:43.215 --> 00:29:46.711
Spectacles, testicles,
watch and wallet.

408
00:29:46.811 --> 00:29:48.309
What are you laughing at?

409
00:29:48.609 --> 00:29:49.808
I'm on my way.

410
00:29:50.008 --> 00:29:52.405
- Dad says to call us collect.
- What?

411
00:29:52.505 --> 00:29:54.104
Dad says to call us collect.

412
00:29:54.503 --> 00:29:56.601
- That's nice of him.
- Tell us how you get on.

413
00:29:57.300 --> 00:29:58.299
Thank you.

414
00:29:58.499 --> 00:29:59.998
That's our phone number.

415
00:30:01.396 --> 00:30:04.793
- Do you think you'll break the record?
- Well, I hope so.

416
00:30:05.592 --> 00:30:07.590
Dad doesn't think
you can do it.

417
00:30:09.688 --> 00:30:11.087
Is that what he said?

418
00:30:11.586 --> 00:30:13.384
He said everyone thinks that.

419
00:30:14.084 --> 00:30:15.282
Well...

420
00:30:16.681 --> 00:30:17.780
Except me.

421
00:30:23.175 --> 00:30:25.572
You're a good boy, Tom.

422
00:30:29.868 --> 00:30:31.666
I'll tell you something, son.

423
00:30:31.966 --> 00:30:35.862
If you don't follow through on your
dreams, you might as well be a vegetable.

424
00:30:37.660 --> 00:30:39.358
What type of vegetable?

425
00:30:39.758 --> 00:30:41.057
I don't know...

426
00:30:41.756 --> 00:30:42.655
a cabbage.

427
00:30:43.754 --> 00:30:44.953
Yeah...

428
00:30:45.153 --> 00:30:46.451
<i>a cabbage.</i>

429
00:30:48.349 --> 00:30:50.397
There you are.
Don't lose it, will you?

430
00:30:50.398 --> 00:30:52.445
- I promise I'll look after it.
- Right.

431
00:30:54.643 --> 00:30:57.640
So keep an eye on the place
for me won't you, Tom.

432
00:30:58.140 --> 00:30:59.139
And...

433
00:31:00.737 --> 00:31:02.635
don't forget
to feed the fowls.

434
00:31:02.735 --> 00:31:04.233
- That's my job.
- Yeah.

435
00:31:04.433 --> 00:31:05.431
And...

436
00:31:05.432 --> 00:31:08.629
you can give
the eggs to Mum and...

437
00:31:08.929 --> 00:31:10.427
what else is there?

438
00:31:11.226 --> 00:31:12.225
Oh, yes...

439
00:31:12.825 --> 00:31:17.121
you can pee on my lemon tree
for me if you like, while I'm away.

440
00:31:17.121 --> 00:31:20.018
And there's nothing wrong
with peeing on your lemon tree...

441
00:31:20.118 --> 00:31:24.014
as Confucius used to say, it's the best
natural fertilizer in the world.

442
00:31:24.213 --> 00:31:26.711
- Who's Confucius?
- He's some bloke who lives up in Dunedin.

443
00:31:27.310 --> 00:31:28.809
Thanks for you help, chaps.

444
00:31:29.009 --> 00:31:30.607
- Good luck, Burt.
- Thanks, Jeff.

445
00:31:30.707 --> 00:31:33.304
- You show them over there in the States.
- I will.

446
00:31:33.504 --> 00:31:34.503
Take it easy, Burt.

447
00:31:34.603 --> 00:31:37.200
That's not one of the things
I'm planning on doing, George.

448
00:31:37.300 --> 00:31:38.549
Cheerio, love.

449
00:31:38.550 --> 00:31:39.798
Good luck.

450
00:31:39.898 --> 00:31:41.196
Cheerio, my friend.

451
00:31:41.596 --> 00:31:44.293
If you don't go when you wanna go
when you do go, you'll find you're gone.

452
00:31:44.393 --> 00:31:45.892
- I'll see ya.
- See ya, Burt.

453
00:31:46.391 --> 00:31:47.590
Bye, Burt.

454
00:31:48.090 --> 00:31:49.488
- Good luck.
- Cheerio.

455
00:31:50.187 --> 00:31:50.987
See ya, Burt.

456
00:32:04.573 --> 00:32:05.472
Look at that!

457
00:32:15.762 --> 00:32:19.258
Well, Fran,
I'm finally on my way.

458
00:32:22.755 --> 00:32:26.151
I thought some more
of the blokes from the club...

459
00:32:26.251 --> 00:32:28.549
would have dropped
by to see me off.

460
00:32:29.148 --> 00:32:31.546
Well, they probably had
to work today.

461
00:32:31.846 --> 00:32:33.444
Yeah. Yeah, that's right.

462
00:32:34.443 --> 00:32:36.941
Yeah, young Tom tells me...

463
00:32:38.040 --> 00:32:39.838
that no one thinks
I can do it.

464
00:32:40.337 --> 00:32:43.834
- Do you think I can do it, Fran?
- I don't know, Burt.

465
00:32:44.034 --> 00:32:46.231
I don't think it really matters
one way or the other.

466
00:32:52.225 --> 00:32:54.823
You know, I read something once,
years ago.

467
00:32:56.121 --> 00:32:58.020
I learnt it off by heart.

468
00:32:59.318 --> 00:33:02.515
It was Theodore Roosevelt
said it...

469
00:33:03.614 --> 00:33:07.410
it's not
the critic that counts...

470
00:33:07.610 --> 00:33:11.806
not the man who points out
how the strong man stumbles...

471
00:33:12.006 --> 00:33:16.801
or where the doer of deeds
could have done them better.

472
00:33:19.098 --> 00:33:23.194
The credit belongs to the man
who is actually in the arena.

473
00:33:32.485 --> 00:33:34.483
Wind your window down!
Down.

474
00:33:34.683 --> 00:33:36.081
What?

475
00:33:36.481 --> 00:33:37.979
Some beer money.

476
00:33:37.980 --> 00:33:40.177
- What?
- Some beer money.

477
00:33:41.076 --> 00:33:42.575
I don't drink.

478
00:33:43.474 --> 00:33:45.072
Good luck.

479
00:33:45.272 --> 00:33:46.571
- You go well.
- Thanks, mate.

480
00:33:46.771 --> 00:33:48.269
You show 'em Kiwis can fly.

481
00:33:48.369 --> 00:33:51.366
Yeah, I'll bring you back
the Statue of Liberty.

482
00:33:52.065 --> 00:33:53.364
Good on you mate,
thanks a lot.

483
00:34:11.946 --> 00:34:13.544
Hey, not so fast!

484
00:34:16.041 --> 00:34:17.140
Crikey!

485
00:34:18.839 --> 00:34:20.237
Take it easy, mate!

486
00:34:22.835 --> 00:34:24.233
I thought it was a goner.

487
00:34:31.626 --> 00:34:32.925
Better get going.

488
00:34:32.925 --> 00:34:34.223
Yeah, alright...

489
00:34:34.823 --> 00:34:37.520
take care of the old jalopy,
won't you?

490
00:34:39.118 --> 00:34:41.015
- You look after yourself.
- I will.

491
00:34:41.016 --> 00:34:42.715
You've got your pills
and everything, right?

492
00:34:42.716 --> 00:34:44.613
Yeah, yeah, right as rain.

493
00:34:49.508 --> 00:34:52.505
- You come back in one piece.
- I will, cheerio.

494
00:35:02.695 --> 00:35:03.993
Where's the Captain?

495
00:35:04.093 --> 00:35:05.392
Down below.

496
00:35:05.592 --> 00:35:07.390
- Down the gangway there.
- Thanks.

497
00:35:08.589 --> 00:35:09.987
There we are.

498
00:35:10.287 --> 00:35:12.185
I'm looking for the Captain.

499
00:35:12.685 --> 00:35:13.884
That's me.

500
00:35:15.082 --> 00:35:17.080
My name's Burt Munro.

501
00:35:19.878 --> 00:35:23.674
I'm supposed to do a job to work
my passage to Los Angeles.

502
00:35:23.874 --> 00:35:26.271
- Yeah, well, I hope you can cook.
- Cook?

503
00:35:28.469 --> 00:35:30.467
- I'll give it a go.
- There's the galley.

504
00:35:35.162 --> 00:35:35.961
Crikey!

505
00:35:37.360 --> 00:35:38.759
Who does the dishes, mate?

506
00:35:39.458 --> 00:35:40.557
You.

507
00:35:46.051 --> 00:35:47.450
Smells good.

508
00:35:47.750 --> 00:35:49.348
What do you have
for us today, Burt?

509
00:35:49.648 --> 00:35:51.446
It's good Kiwi tucker.

510
00:35:54.043 --> 00:35:56.541
Don't let Burt see you
doing that.

511
00:35:56.940 --> 00:35:59.638
Here, don't spoil it
with all that sauce.

512
00:36:00.137 --> 00:36:01.836
- Sorry, Burt.
- Stone the crows!

513
00:36:07.330 --> 00:36:08.628
Are you going to watch
the movie, Burt?

514
00:36:08.629 --> 00:36:11.326
- What's that?
- Are you going to watch the movie?

515
00:36:12.425 --> 00:36:14.723
- What's it called?
- Broken Barrier.

516
00:36:16.321 --> 00:36:19.318
- It's supposed to be good.
- Is Jane Russell in it?

517
00:36:20.017 --> 00:36:21.915
There's a spare seat
over here, Burt.

518
00:36:29.708 --> 00:36:30.707
Smoke?

519
00:36:31.006 --> 00:36:33.404
- No. Not for me, mate.
- You don't smoke Burt?

520
00:36:33.405 --> 00:36:35.802
No, I don't
and that's why people say to me...

521
00:36:36.101 --> 00:36:37.949
how do you keep going
at your age, Burt...

522
00:36:37.950 --> 00:36:39.797
and I say,
well because I don't smoke...

523
00:36:39.798 --> 00:36:42.595
so I'm telling you young monkeys,
don't smoke.

524
00:36:43.194 --> 00:36:45.991
You can laugh,
but my Dad said...

525
00:36:46.191 --> 00:36:48.389
why contaminate your lungs
with tobacco smoke?

526
00:36:48.589 --> 00:36:51.686
The only thing you accomplish with
smoking is destroying your lungs...

527
00:36:51.687 --> 00:36:54.283
- and shortening your life.
- Kill the lights.

528
00:36:58.179 --> 00:36:59.278
Is Jane Russell in this?

529
00:37:00.477 --> 00:37:01.776
Go well, Burt.

530
00:37:03.174 --> 00:37:05.172
- Thanks, mate.

531
00:37:11.965 --> 00:37:13.564
- Good luck to you, Burt.
- Thanks.

532
00:37:13.764 --> 00:37:15.562
Remember what I said.
Don't smoke.

533
00:37:16.361 --> 00:37:17.360
I'm trying.

534
00:37:17.660 --> 00:37:19.058
Cheerio, mates. See ya.

535
00:37:20.657 --> 00:37:22.954
Welcome to the United States.
Customs to the left.

536
00:37:23.054 --> 00:37:24.653
Thank you, good to be here.

537
00:37:25.152 --> 00:37:26.151
G'day.

538
00:37:32.645 --> 00:37:33.644
G'day.

539
00:37:33.943 --> 00:37:36.441
Please, stand behind the yellow line
until you are called, sir.

540
00:37:36.541 --> 00:37:37.540
What's that?

541
00:37:37.640 --> 00:37:40.137
- Behind the yellow line.
- Yellow line?

542
00:37:50.327 --> 00:37:51.326
G'day.

543
00:37:51.426 --> 00:37:53.923
Passport and customs declaration,
please sir.

544
00:37:55.222 --> 00:37:56.521
There you are.

545
00:38:01.915 --> 00:38:04.113
How long do you intend
to stay in the United States?

546
00:38:04.313 --> 00:38:08.509
However long it takes me to get
to Bonneville and back.

547
00:38:08.709 --> 00:38:10.706
And the purpose of your visit?

548
00:38:10.707 --> 00:38:14.103
To set a land speed record
on my Indian.

549
00:38:15.202 --> 00:38:16.101
Indian?

550
00:38:16.601 --> 00:38:17.700
Mr. Munro...

551
00:38:17.899 --> 00:38:19.997
- So this is your first time to America?
- Yes, sir.

552
00:38:20.197 --> 00:38:22.894
You gave some rather odd answers
to the Officer...

553
00:38:23.194 --> 00:38:24.992
so we just have a few further
questions we'd like to ask you.

554
00:38:25.092 --> 00:38:28.788
- Well, fire away.
- Well, let's go over again what you said.

555
00:38:29.188 --> 00:38:31.885
Now what exactly do you intend to do
here in the United States?

556
00:38:32.185 --> 00:38:33.983
Well, set a land speed record.

557
00:38:35.082 --> 00:38:38.179
- And how do you intend to do that, sir?
- On my motorcycle.

558
00:38:38.479 --> 00:38:41.775
It's in the hold of the ship
at the moment and...

559
00:38:41.975 --> 00:38:46.671
they're going to unload it tomorrow.
It's an Indian, a 1920 Indian Scout...

560
00:38:47.570 --> 00:38:49.068
modified somewhat.

561
00:38:50.067 --> 00:38:50.966
You know what?

562
00:38:51.566 --> 00:38:53.863
- I think I've read about your bike.
- Yeah?

563
00:38:54.063 --> 00:38:57.160
Yeah, it was in Popular Mechanics,
a couple of years ago.

564
00:38:57.360 --> 00:38:58.958
That's right, that's me.

565
00:38:59.158 --> 00:39:02.355
A Leslie Hobbs from Christchurch
sent that story.

566
00:39:02.555 --> 00:39:05.352
What was it?
Fastest motorcycle in Australia?

567
00:39:05.552 --> 00:39:07.350
Yeah, and in New Zealand.

568
00:39:09.747 --> 00:39:11.845
Well, I guess you're legitimate,
Mr. Munro.

569
00:39:12.145 --> 00:39:14.842
It sounds like we should be very
honoured to have you here in America.

570
00:39:15.042 --> 00:39:17.540
- Well, thank you.
- We're going to give you six months...

571
00:39:17.739 --> 00:39:19.737
that should be time enough
to get the job done.

572
00:39:21.935 --> 00:39:24.233
- Welcome to the USA.
- Thank you very much.

573
00:39:24.433 --> 00:39:26.131
- Good luck, sir.
- Thank you.

574
00:39:33.424 --> 00:39:34.922
- Gears in the trunk.
- What?

575
00:39:35.122 --> 00:39:36.521
Bags in the back.

576
00:39:37.020 --> 00:39:38.419
Bag, back!

577
00:39:38.519 --> 00:39:41.516
Don't worry about me,
I'll do it myself.

578
00:39:42.015 --> 00:39:43.314
Strewth!

579
00:39:56.800 --> 00:39:58.599
Sit in the back, in the back!

580
00:39:58.898 --> 00:40:00.896
- What?
- You, in the back!

581
00:40:02.495 --> 00:40:06.291
Tell you something, mate,
you don't want to get old around here.

582
00:40:09.288 --> 00:40:10.487
Ta ra.

583
00:40:13.084 --> 00:40:14.682
- Where to?
- What?

584
00:40:14.982 --> 00:40:17.379
- Where to?
- Hollywood.

585
00:40:17.380 --> 00:40:20.776
Yeah, I want to go to Hollywood,
I want to see the film stars.

586
00:40:21.176 --> 00:40:23.374
Okay, we go to Hollywood.

587
00:40:23.773 --> 00:40:25.372
Where in Hollywood?

588
00:40:26.071 --> 00:40:29.568
A motel on Sunset Boulevard...

589
00:40:30.267 --> 00:40:32.065
I hear that's a pretty great street.

590
00:40:32.265 --> 00:40:35.262
I don't know who you talking to lately.
Which motel?

591
00:40:36.561 --> 00:40:38.059
Recommend one.

592
00:40:38.359 --> 00:40:40.856
Come on man, what do you think
I am, an encyclopaedia?

593
00:40:41.056 --> 00:40:44.752
Drop me somewhere
and I'll sort it out myself.

594
00:40:52.944 --> 00:40:55.142
Must have a bit
electricity bill here.

595
00:40:59.438 --> 00:41:00.736
Firestone...

596
00:41:01.735 --> 00:41:02.734
Shell.

597
00:41:04.732 --> 00:41:08.529
It's all about cars, isn't it?
I've never seen so many cars.

598
00:41:08.928 --> 00:41:12.525
- You say something, man?
- I said I've never seen so many cars.

599
00:41:12.824 --> 00:41:15.222
Got to get around somehow.

600
00:41:20.017 --> 00:41:23.114
Look, there's a bowling alley.
Do you bowl?

601
00:41:29.308 --> 00:41:31.306
What's he honking his horn about?

602
00:41:34.602 --> 00:41:37.000
Jesus!
Crikey, did you see that?

603
00:41:38.099 --> 00:41:40.097
That blokes backing into that
geaser's car.

604
00:41:40.996 --> 00:41:42.495
He's crazy, he's nuts.

605
00:41:43.394 --> 00:41:44.992
He did it again.

606
00:41:46.291 --> 00:41:48.688
Don't stare, there's a lot of
crazy people in this town.

607
00:41:48.988 --> 00:41:50.786
I've never seen anything
like that before.

608
00:42:01.875 --> 00:42:03.973
- This should do...
- What's the damage?

609
00:42:04.672 --> 00:42:06.071
28 dollar, plus bag...

610
00:42:06.471 --> 00:42:08.269
- 29 dollar.
- What?

611
00:42:09.767 --> 00:42:12.564
Did you just say
what I thought you said?

612
00:42:12.664 --> 00:42:14.862
- Are you deaf?
- What?

613
00:42:14.962 --> 00:42:18.359
- Are you deaf?
- Yeah, I am a bit deaf, but I'm not stupid.

614
00:42:18.459 --> 00:42:21.356
- How much did you say it was?
- 29 dollar.

615
00:42:21.555 --> 00:42:25.951
No, I don't want to buy the cab, mate.
I just want to pay the fare, that's all.

616
00:42:25.952 --> 00:42:27.649
- Where you from?
- What?

617
00:42:27.849 --> 00:42:30.946
- You a British?
- No, you must be joking...

618
00:42:31.146 --> 00:42:33.444
I'm no Pommie,
I'm from New Zealand.

619
00:42:33.643 --> 00:42:35.042
Well, this is America.

620
00:42:35.941 --> 00:42:38.838
And the fare, right there on the meter,
29 dollar.

621
00:42:39.238 --> 00:42:41.835
Open your wallet
and let the moths out.

622
00:42:42.035 --> 00:42:43.434
I'm doing it, I'm doing it.

623
00:42:44.033 --> 00:42:46.630
There you go, 29 dollars.

624
00:42:46.830 --> 00:42:48.728
- No, don't forget the tip.
- What?

625
00:42:48.928 --> 00:42:51.226
Yes, we tip in America.

626
00:42:51.525 --> 00:42:52.325
Ten percent.

627
00:42:52.425 --> 00:42:54.223
- How much?
- Ten percent.

628
00:42:56.121 --> 00:42:57.619
Oh yeah, there you go, ten cents.

629
00:43:06.311 --> 00:43:07.809
Excuse me, sir.

630
00:43:08.009 --> 00:43:10.107
- You look like a generous man, sir.
- What?

631
00:43:10.307 --> 00:43:12.105
- You look like a generous man.
- Oh do I?

632
00:43:12.305 --> 00:43:15.601
Yes you do. Would you like to buy
a flower to give to someone special?

633
00:43:15.901 --> 00:43:17.899
Well,
sorry I don't have any cash.

634
00:43:18.199 --> 00:43:20.397
Don't worry,
the money goes to a good cause.

635
00:43:20.596 --> 00:43:23.194
It's for an organization
that helps needy people.

636
00:43:23.493 --> 00:43:25.392
Oh alright, well, how much is it?

637
00:43:25.691 --> 00:43:27.989
- Just give what you can afford.
- Alright, well.

638
00:43:29.887 --> 00:43:31.984
They all look the same to me.
They're all green.

639
00:43:31.985 --> 00:43:34.682
- Yes, that's why we call them greenbacks.
- That looks like a one.

640
00:43:34.982 --> 00:43:36.381
- Look there's one.
- No, that's a ten.

641
00:43:36.480 --> 00:43:38.279
- Thanks, you have a good day.
- No, that's a ten.

642
00:43:38.478 --> 00:43:40.377
Hey come on miss, that's a ten.

643
00:43:40.776 --> 00:43:41.975
I didn't want to pay that much.

644
00:43:42.275 --> 00:43:43.673
Hey, come back.

645
00:43:47.568 --> 00:43:48.567
Crikey.

646
00:43:48.568 --> 00:43:50.067
- Hey baby.
- What do you want?

647
00:43:50.267 --> 00:43:51.565
- You wanna go?
- Go where?

648
00:43:52.764 --> 00:43:55.162
- Go inside.
- I'm going inside.

649
00:43:55.961 --> 00:43:57.859
I'll take you around the world.

650
00:43:58.059 --> 00:43:59.857
I've just come from halfway
around the world.

651
00:43:59.957 --> 00:44:01.655
15 bucks, baby.

652
00:44:01.656 --> 00:44:02.954
15 bucks.

653
00:44:03.154 --> 00:44:04.952
No, sorry, go away.

654
00:44:12.145 --> 00:44:13.044
Hello.

655
00:44:18.239 --> 00:44:21.435
- I need a room.
- A room will cost you five bucks an hour.

656
00:44:21.436 --> 00:44:23.533
I'm planning on staying
a wee bit longer than that.

657
00:44:23.633 --> 00:44:26.331
- How long?
- I don't know, a couple of days I guess.

658
00:44:26.430 --> 00:44:28.528
- Double occupancy?
- What?

659
00:44:28.828 --> 00:44:30.227
Double occupancy?

660
00:44:30.426 --> 00:44:32.824
No, just me, myself and I.

661
00:44:33.623 --> 00:44:36.820
Will it cost a lot because
I can't afford a lot.

662
00:44:38.119 --> 00:44:40.217
- You a member of Triple A?
- What?

663
00:44:40.416 --> 00:44:42.814
- Are you a Triple A member?
- Never heard of them.

664
00:44:43.114 --> 00:44:44.313
Never heard of Triple A?

665
00:44:44.512 --> 00:44:47.809
No Miss Brittle Britches,
I have not heard of Triple A.

666
00:44:49.308 --> 00:44:51.306
Okay, let's just say
you are a member, doll.

667
00:44:51.306 --> 00:44:53.304
- Alright.
- That'll save you ten percent.

668
00:44:54.602 --> 00:44:56.600
How does 22 bucks a night sound?

669
00:44:57.000 --> 00:44:59.098
That much? Is that cheap?

670
00:45:00.197 --> 00:45:01.595
Honey, that's cheaper than cheap.

671
00:45:04.892 --> 00:45:07.789
- What's your name?
- Tina Washington.

672
00:45:07.989 --> 00:45:09.287
Well, Tina Washington,

673
00:45:09.288 --> 00:45:11.885
I want you to have this,
it might cheer you up a bit.

674
00:45:12.185 --> 00:45:14.283
Get some of that muck
off your pluck.

675
00:45:14.782 --> 00:45:16.081
Well, thank you.

676
00:45:16.680 --> 00:45:18.978
That's the first nice thing
that's happened round here all week.

677
00:45:18.979 --> 00:45:20.376
You're welcome.

678
00:45:20.676 --> 00:45:23.673
My name's Burt Munro.
From New Zealand.

679
00:45:23.773 --> 00:45:25.272
I'm from down under.

680
00:45:25.471 --> 00:45:27.569
Well, hello, Burt Munro
from New Zealand down under.

681
00:45:27.869 --> 00:45:29.967
I tell you,
I've had a heck of a night.

682
00:45:30.666 --> 00:45:32.265
Welcome to Hollyweird.

683
00:46:24.113 --> 00:46:25.511
Hello?

684
00:46:25.811 --> 00:46:27.010
Anybody home?

685
00:46:29.108 --> 00:46:31.106
- Hello, Tina.
- Good morning, Burt.

686
00:46:31.405 --> 00:46:32.904
You still here?

687
00:46:34.203 --> 00:46:37.100
That's why you were
so crabby last night.

688
00:46:37.299 --> 00:46:38.598
Don't you ever get any sleep?

689
00:46:38.898 --> 00:46:40.396
I work a night shift.

690
00:46:40.596 --> 00:46:43.094
I'm out of here as soon as James
turns up and he's late.

691
00:46:44.292 --> 00:46:47.389
Yeah, could you phone
this number for me?

692
00:46:47.789 --> 00:46:51.186
Yeah, it's a shipping company
and they've got a big box of mine...

693
00:46:51.485 --> 00:46:54.682
and I want to know how
to arrange to get it.

694
00:46:56.980 --> 00:46:59.078
No, you talk to them,
they'll never get my accent.

695
00:46:59.277 --> 00:47:01.775
Okay, what do you want me
to ask them? One moment please.

696
00:47:01.875 --> 00:47:06.570
Ask them when a Burt Munro's box
containing the motorcycle...

697
00:47:06.571 --> 00:47:07.769
will be ready for pick up.

698
00:47:08.568 --> 00:47:11.066
Hello, I'm calling
for Mr. Burt Munro.

699
00:47:11.166 --> 00:47:13.963
Yes, he'd like to know when the box
containing his motorcycle...

700
00:47:13.964 --> 00:47:16.061
<i>- will be available for pick up.
- What ship?</i>

701
00:47:16.660 --> 00:47:19.058
- What ship?
- Rangatira from New Zealand.

702
00:47:19.257 --> 00:47:21.355
The Rangatira from New Zealand.

703
00:47:21.555 --> 00:47:23.253
<i>- It's arrived.
- So he can claim it?</i>

704
00:47:25.251 --> 00:47:27.649
Tomorrow from the Long Beach
customs holding area.

705
00:47:27.949 --> 00:47:29.847
Okay, thank you, I'll tell him.
Bye-bye.

706
00:47:30.147 --> 00:47:31.745
That was pretty fast.

707
00:47:32.045 --> 00:47:33.543
You're late.

708
00:47:35.741 --> 00:47:39.138
I can't stand another minute in
this place. Let me buy you breakfast.

709
00:47:42.534 --> 00:47:43.833
Well, this is great.

710
00:47:44.232 --> 00:47:47.929
You know, I've never seen
a menu with photographs before.

711
00:47:49.227 --> 00:47:50.726
- Are you ready to order, sir?
- What?

712
00:47:51.026 --> 00:47:52.824
- Are you ready?
- Oh yes...

713
00:47:54.023 --> 00:47:57.719
I think the Double Delight,
that's for me.

714
00:47:58.418 --> 00:48:00.216
- How would you like your eggs?
- What?

715
00:48:00.416 --> 00:48:02.015
How would you like your eggs?

716
00:48:02.814 --> 00:48:04.013
Well, I'd like them cooked.

717
00:48:04.912 --> 00:48:07.809
Sunny side up? Over easy?

718
00:48:08.208 --> 00:48:11.505
- I don't know, whatever you recommend.
- Over easy's best.

719
00:48:12.304 --> 00:48:13.803
Alright, eggs over easy.

720
00:48:14.103 --> 00:48:15.301
Make that two.

721
00:48:15.601 --> 00:48:18.298
Over easy.
I must remember that.

722
00:48:18.498 --> 00:48:21.295
Yeah, I like this American
breakfast thing.

723
00:48:21.995 --> 00:48:22.994
It's good.

724
00:48:24.692 --> 00:48:29.088
So my girl, where's the best place
for me to get a used car?

725
00:48:29.287 --> 00:48:30.586
The valley.

726
00:48:31.086 --> 00:48:33.084
After breakfast I could
take you there.

727
00:48:33.183 --> 00:48:34.182
Oh, thank you.

728
00:48:36.180 --> 00:48:37.879
And I'm not a girl.

729
00:48:39.977 --> 00:48:40.976
I'm a boy.

730
00:48:46.071 --> 00:48:48.468
I thought there was something
a little odd about you.

731
00:48:48.469 --> 00:48:51.365
But hey,
you're still a sweetheart.

732
00:48:54.262 --> 00:48:55.161
Yep.

733
00:49:09.347 --> 00:49:10.546
Thanks a million, Tina.

734
00:49:10.846 --> 00:49:12.944
Hey,
there are stacks of cars here.

735
00:49:13.643 --> 00:49:15.941
- I'll be back in the motel later on.
- Bye.

736
00:49:17.139 --> 00:49:18.238
Bye.

737
00:49:22.733 --> 00:49:24.431
Buenos diaz!

738
00:49:24.432 --> 00:49:25.831
How may I help you, sir?

739
00:49:26.130 --> 00:49:30.027
Yeah, I want to buy a car,
a cheap car, a very cheap car.

740
00:49:30.027 --> 00:49:32.224
Well, you've come
to the right place, amigo.

741
00:49:32.624 --> 00:49:36.920
In fact, if you can find cars like this
any cheaper, they're probably stolen.

742
00:49:37.119 --> 00:49:40.516
My name's Burt, Burt Munro
from New Zealand. Nice to meet you.

743
00:49:40.816 --> 00:49:43.313
I'm Fernando from El Salvador,
nice to meet you, Mr. Munro.

744
00:49:43.413 --> 00:49:46.011
- You can call me Burt.
- Okay, Mr. Burt.

745
00:49:46.610 --> 00:49:49.807
So how much were you looking
to spend here Mr. Burt?

746
00:49:49.808 --> 00:49:51.105
Not a lot Fernando...

747
00:49:51.405 --> 00:49:54.003
I haven't got much left after
the cab ride I took yesterday.

748
00:49:55.301 --> 00:49:57.099
You want 399 for this?

749
00:49:58.098 --> 00:49:59.797
It sounds a bit sick.

750
00:49:59.997 --> 00:50:01.595
Well, what would you offer me?

751
00:50:01.995 --> 00:50:04.892
Listen, I'll give you 200
if you'll do me a favour.

752
00:50:05.691 --> 00:50:08.588
Throw in the use
of your workshop...

753
00:50:08.788 --> 00:50:11.285
and some of that junk
I see lying around...

754
00:50:11.985 --> 00:50:14.682
I've got to knock up
a trailer...

755
00:50:14.982 --> 00:50:17.179
to drag my bike over
to Bonneville.

756
00:50:17.379 --> 00:50:19.377
That's not a favour,
325 is a favour.

757
00:50:19.577 --> 00:50:21.775
No, 225.

758
00:50:22.774 --> 00:50:25.371
You're a tough customer, Mr. Burt,
but I like you...

759
00:50:25.671 --> 00:50:28.968
I'm going to give it to you for 250
and you can use the workshop...

760
00:50:29.067 --> 00:50:31.465
but only at night
and keep the noise down.

761
00:50:31.466 --> 00:50:32.164
What about tonight?

762
00:50:32.564 --> 00:50:34.062
Yeah, yeah, tonight's OK.

763
00:50:34.362 --> 00:50:37.959
Stop the car, let's get
this thing running properly.

764
00:50:51.745 --> 00:50:53.143
There that sounds better.

765
00:50:55.041 --> 00:50:58.138
- Let me drive.
- Okay, come on.

766
00:50:58.338 --> 00:51:00.736
She's singing
like a bird now.

767
00:51:01.135 --> 00:51:03.333
Oh, she's a good old girl,
isn't she?

768
00:51:03.533 --> 00:51:04.932
There we are, alright.

769
00:51:11.825 --> 00:51:15.121
- You make a left here, Mr. Burt.
- Alright.

770
00:51:18.918 --> 00:51:21.015
The buggers are in the wrong lane.

771
00:51:21.215 --> 00:51:22.714
Stop the car, stop the car.

772
00:51:24.912 --> 00:51:26.910
Turn, turn, this way.

773
00:51:27.809 --> 00:51:29.407
Stop, stop the car.

774
00:51:31.705 --> 00:51:33.503
Keep your shirt on.

775
00:51:35.601 --> 00:51:38.898
- Scoot over, you stupid old bastard.
- Thought I was back in New Zealand...

776
00:51:38.898 --> 00:51:41.495
we drive on the other side
of the road over there.

777
00:51:41.795 --> 00:51:44.192
Yeah? You're going to get
us all killed.

778
00:51:45.691 --> 00:51:48.538
Well, you're not in New Zealand,
you're in America.

779
00:51:48.539 --> 00:51:51.385
- I know it.
- We drive on the right side of the road.

780
00:52:00.876 --> 00:52:03.972
Now, Burt.
Let me give you some advice.

781
00:52:06.070 --> 00:52:08.768
When you're driving,
not only here in America...

782
00:52:08.868 --> 00:52:10.566
but anywhere's around the world...

783
00:52:10.766 --> 00:52:14.062
the driver should always
be in the centre of the road.

784
00:52:14.462 --> 00:52:17.109
In the centre.
If you're not in the centre...

785
00:52:17.110 --> 00:52:19.757
you're on the wrong side of the road.
Okay?

786
00:52:29.547 --> 00:52:31.445
You want this right here?

787
00:52:34.642 --> 00:52:35.841
That's it.

788
00:52:36.240 --> 00:52:37.439
Yeah, good.

789
00:52:37.839 --> 00:52:38.937
Got it.

790
00:52:39.437 --> 00:52:41.235
It's 3 am in the morning.

791
00:52:41.435 --> 00:52:44.432
Yeah, time flies
when you're having fun, doesn't it?

792
00:52:45.431 --> 00:52:48.428
You know, when I told you that
you could use the workshop at night...

793
00:52:48.429 --> 00:52:50.426
I didn't mean all night.
My wife's gonna kill me.

794
00:52:51.025 --> 00:52:53.723
You take yourself off home
and I'll have a snooze...

795
00:52:53.724 --> 00:52:56.320
in the back of the car
and you know, mate...

796
00:52:56.520 --> 00:52:58.916
I'll lock up the place
before I go to sleep.

797
00:52:58.917 --> 00:53:02.414
Seems to me like a whole lot of effort
to sell a lousy 250 dollar motorcar.

798
00:53:03.013 --> 00:53:05.910
Okay, Mr. Burt, you pull the door down.
Have a good night.

799
00:53:07.009 --> 00:53:11.805
Fernando.
Where do I take a leak around here?

800
00:53:12.604 --> 00:53:14.102
- Leak?
- Yeah, a pee...

801
00:53:14.402 --> 00:53:16.400
trouble with the old prostrate,
you know.

802
00:53:16.700 --> 00:53:19.996
Yeah, go straight through those doors,
there's a door there that says Caballero...

803
00:53:20.496 --> 00:53:21.395
Alright.

804
00:53:22.394 --> 00:53:24.392
Well, I'll see you in the morning,
early okay?

805
00:53:24.492 --> 00:53:25.691
Good night.

806
00:53:26.490 --> 00:53:27.289
Where were we?

807
00:53:31.485 --> 00:53:32.084
Burt?

808
00:53:34.382 --> 00:53:35.980
Buenos diaz, Mr. Burt.

809
00:53:39.477 --> 00:53:41.775
- So did you get it all finished?
- Yeah.

810
00:53:41.974 --> 00:53:46.070
All I need to do is find a couple
of wheels and I'll be ready to roll.

811
00:53:46.370 --> 00:53:49.267
Well, you know, I have some wheels
in the back you can have...

812
00:53:49.268 --> 00:53:51.565
- if you just do me a favour.
- Say the word.

813
00:53:54.961 --> 00:53:56.460
Crank her now, Fernando.

814
00:53:57.559 --> 00:53:58.558
Good.

815
00:54:00.156 --> 00:54:01.255
- Burt?
- Yeah?

816
00:54:01.655 --> 00:54:02.754
You're a god damned genius.

817
00:54:02.953 --> 00:54:03.852
Thank you.

818
00:54:04.052 --> 00:54:06.150
Hey listen, why you gotta go?

819
00:54:06.350 --> 00:54:08.148
Why don't you stick around here a while?
I'll pay you well.

820
00:54:08.348 --> 00:54:10.646
Sorry, mate, I've got to get
to Bonneville by the 23rd...

821
00:54:10.845 --> 00:54:14.642
that's when speed week starts and
you know, gotta hit the road.

822
00:54:14.941 --> 00:54:17.938
- Well, you've always got a job here.
- Thanks mate, I'll see ya.

823
00:54:18.238 --> 00:54:19.936
- Best of luck to you.
- Ta ra.

824
00:54:21.135 --> 00:54:23.033
This guy is really good.

825
00:54:34.722 --> 00:54:36.120
Hello, love.

826
00:54:36.320 --> 00:54:38.118
I was worried about you.

827
00:54:38.418 --> 00:54:41.415
Housekeeping said you didn't
sleep in your bed all night.

828
00:54:41.715 --> 00:54:43.213
Do I get a discount for that?

829
00:54:43.812 --> 00:54:44.810
I doubt it.

830
00:54:44.811 --> 00:54:47.309
I need you to show me on a map
how to get to Long Beach...

831
00:54:47.409 --> 00:54:50.306
- so I can pick up my bike today.
- I'm finished here in 15 minutes.

832
00:54:50.406 --> 00:54:51.405
I'll come with you.

833
00:54:55.101 --> 00:54:57.998
Not a bad set of wheels
for 250 bucks eh?

834
00:54:58.098 --> 00:55:00.296
- You sure it'll make it to Utah?
- Yeah.

835
00:55:00.895 --> 00:55:03.693
This old girl will get you
to New Zealand and back.

836
00:55:04.192 --> 00:55:05.291
Here...

837
00:55:05.591 --> 00:55:07.389
- hop in my fair, lady.
- Thank you.

838
00:55:10.086 --> 00:55:12.484
The bloke who sold me this car,
he gave me a good tip...

839
00:55:12.584 --> 00:55:15.980
he said always remember
that the driver, that's me...

840
00:55:16.080 --> 00:55:18.578
should be on the centre
of the road.

841
00:55:18.678 --> 00:55:20.176
- Look out, look out!
- Alright.

842
00:55:20.476 --> 00:55:24.272
In New Zealand we always drive
on the other side of the street.

843
00:55:25.371 --> 00:55:27.469
- You do?
- Yeah, sorry about that.

844
00:55:29.067 --> 00:55:30.265
Do you want me to drive?

845
00:55:30.266 --> 00:55:32.564
No, it's alright,
I have to get used to it, haven't I?

846
00:55:35.760 --> 00:55:37.559
This should be customs
right here.

847
00:55:37.560 --> 00:55:38.558
Right.

848
00:55:44.951 --> 00:55:46.849
- Hello.
- May I help you, sir?

849
00:55:47.049 --> 00:55:50.845
Yeah, my name's Burt Munro and
I've come to pick up my motorcycle...

850
00:55:51.145 --> 00:55:53.643
I came into port two days ago
from New Zealand...

851
00:55:53.942 --> 00:55:56.939
and on a freighter
called Rangatira...

852
00:55:57.139 --> 00:55:59.637
and I was told to come here
to clear it through customs.

853
00:56:00.935 --> 00:56:02.933
- Mr. Munro.
- Yeah, Munro...

854
00:56:03.233 --> 00:56:04.731
M U N R O.

855
00:56:07.529 --> 00:56:09.726
- Wait here a moment, sir.
- Thank you.

856
00:56:13.223 --> 00:56:15.920
Mr. Munro is here
for that damaged shipment.

857
00:56:19.117 --> 00:56:21.115
- Mr. Moonro.
- Munro.

858
00:56:21.315 --> 00:56:23.812
- Come with me please, to the storage area.
- Is there a problem?

859
00:56:23.813 --> 00:56:25.810
Your consignment
has suffered some damage.

860
00:56:26.510 --> 00:56:27.808
Oh, no.

861
00:56:28.408 --> 00:56:31.704
Why the heck did I bother to paint
these arrows on the side of it then?

862
00:56:32.604 --> 00:56:35.101
That's the way it was
delivered here unfortunately.

863
00:56:35.102 --> 00:56:36.500
Well, what happened to it?

864
00:56:36.699 --> 00:56:38.598
My information is that
ten tons of fertilizer...

865
00:56:38.598 --> 00:56:40.496
was inadvertently
loaded on top of your box...

866
00:56:40.596 --> 00:56:43.093
while it was in the hold. If I was
you I'd sue the shipping company.

867
00:56:43.193 --> 00:56:46.590
Sue? I haven't got time to waste
my bloomin' life suing anybody.

868
00:56:46.590 --> 00:56:48.786
Get some of your blokes to pull...

869
00:56:48.787 --> 00:56:51.185
this right side up so
we can get into the motorcycle...

870
00:56:51.186 --> 00:56:53.583
and see what damage
has been done.

871
00:56:54.981 --> 00:56:56.979
Alright, fellows,
let's get it unwrapped.

872
00:57:00.875 --> 00:57:02.174
The tail looks alright.

873
00:57:07.269 --> 00:57:09.167
No damage so far.

874
00:57:10.965 --> 00:57:12.564
Oh no damage at all.

875
00:57:12.863 --> 00:57:13.862
Good.

876
00:57:14.062 --> 00:57:17.059
- Lucky it was packed so well.
- Yes, it's a blimmin' miracle.

877
00:57:19.157 --> 00:57:22.853
Well, the old Indian lives
to fight another day.

878
00:57:29.846 --> 00:57:31.445
Well, thanks a million, Tina.

879
00:57:31.545 --> 00:57:34.042
I don't know what I would have done
without you today...

880
00:57:34.043 --> 00:57:35.740
you're the real salt of the earth,
you know?

881
00:57:36.140 --> 00:57:38.937
Are you sure you wouldn't like
to come home for dinner tonight?

882
00:57:38.938 --> 00:57:40.635
- I can't, love.
- I could cook you a meal.

883
00:57:40.735 --> 00:57:43.433
I've got to get this show on the road,
get out of Dodge as they say.

884
00:57:43.932 --> 00:57:46.130
Okay, my good friend
from Kiwi land.

885
00:57:46.330 --> 00:57:48.328
- You stay in touch, won't you?
- I will.

886
00:57:48.827 --> 00:57:50.226
Here's my phone number.

887
00:57:50.625 --> 00:57:53.223
- Call me and tell me how you're doing.
- I will. Can I call collect?

888
00:57:53.922 --> 00:57:55.121
You can try.

889
00:58:01.614 --> 00:58:04.512
- It's a good job I think you're a woman.
- I am a woman.

890
00:58:04.711 --> 00:58:07.109
Yeah, right. Ta ra love, see ya.

891
00:58:34.981 --> 00:58:36.380
- Morning.
- Morning.

892
00:58:38.777 --> 00:58:40.376
Fill her up, would you please?

893
00:58:40.476 --> 00:58:41.874
Regular or Ethol?

894
00:58:42.973 --> 00:58:44.372
Who's Ethol?

895
00:58:45.171 --> 00:58:46.669
Alright...

896
00:58:47.269 --> 00:58:48.567
I'll take Ethol.

897
00:58:54.661 --> 00:58:56.559
- Hello, young fella.
- Hello.

898
00:58:56.759 --> 00:58:59.257
- Is this a rocket ship?
- What?

899
00:58:59.457 --> 00:59:01.055
Is this a rocket ship?

900
00:59:01.654 --> 00:59:02.853
I hope so.

901
00:59:42.414 --> 00:59:43.512
Oh Gosh.

902
00:59:50.306 --> 00:59:52.004
What's happened to you?

903
00:59:56.899 --> 00:59:57.898
Oh well.

904
01:00:01.594 --> 01:00:03.093
Let's have a look at ya.

905
01:00:19.476 --> 01:00:20.675
Got ya!

906
01:00:23.373 --> 01:00:24.571
Come on!

907
01:00:35.860 --> 01:00:38.058
I thought we were going
to make it you and me...

908
01:00:39.057 --> 01:00:40.755
and now look what's happened.

909
01:01:33.802 --> 01:01:35.700
- Hello, mate.
- Got a problem?

910
01:01:35.900 --> 01:01:37.798
Yeah. Am I glad to see you.

911
01:01:38.098 --> 01:01:41.894
Yeah, I've lost a wheel, help me get
my rig back on the road, will you?

912
01:01:42.094 --> 01:01:43.592
Okay, I'll see.

913
01:01:44.192 --> 01:01:46.290
My name's Burt, Burt Munro.

914
01:01:47.388 --> 01:01:48.387
Jake.

915
01:01:48.687 --> 01:01:50.385
- You Indian?
- Yes.

916
01:01:51.285 --> 01:01:54.381
Well, this here could be
the world's fastest Indian.

917
01:01:54.481 --> 01:01:56.080
Well, at least until just now.

918
01:01:56.379 --> 01:01:57.978
She's a bit heavy mind you.

919
01:01:58.178 --> 01:02:00.775
So let's take it easy,
one, two, three.

920
01:02:02.473 --> 01:02:04.172
Right.
You live around here, Jake?

921
01:02:21.454 --> 01:02:24.052
What do you want to ride
that contraption for?

922
01:02:24.551 --> 01:02:26.050
That's a good question.

923
01:02:28.148 --> 01:02:31.944
Well, I guess the reward
is in the doing of it.

924
01:02:33.842 --> 01:02:36.939
Jake, I'm dying for a pee.
Where do I go?

925
01:02:37.139 --> 01:02:39.037
There's a little building
right there.

926
01:02:39.137 --> 01:02:41.634
I've got a touch of prostrate
trouble, you know.

927
01:02:41.934 --> 01:02:43.532
I have similar problems.

928
01:02:44.232 --> 01:02:46.229
I thought you blokes would have...

929
01:02:46.230 --> 01:02:48.228
some magic cures
for that sort of thing.

930
01:02:48.427 --> 01:02:49.726
Well, we have.

931
01:02:50.325 --> 01:02:53.622
One old remedy is ground up
dog balls...

932
01:02:53.822 --> 01:02:57.119
- but I prefer prostrate trouble.
- Yeah, I bet you do, mate.

933
01:03:00.615 --> 01:03:01.814
I got you!

934
01:03:03.712 --> 01:03:06.709
Jake, gotta get going,
gotta hit the road.

935
01:03:07.009 --> 01:03:09.606
- Burt, I have something for you.
- Whats that then?

936
01:03:11.205 --> 01:03:12.603
Whats this?

937
01:03:13.003 --> 01:03:15.500
- For good luck.
- Oh yeah? A piece of j...

938
01:03:15.550 --> 01:03:18.897
I've never worn jewellery before.
Thanks, mate.

939
01:03:18.997 --> 01:03:21.394
I've got something for you too.
Hang about.

940
01:03:23.093 --> 01:03:24.192
Right...

941
01:03:24.691 --> 01:03:25.890
let's see.

942
01:03:29.886 --> 01:03:32.383
I've got this, it's a spare one,
I made it myself.

943
01:03:33.183 --> 01:03:35.780
- What do I do with this?
- You got a hacksaw?

944
01:03:35.980 --> 01:03:38.477
Just slice the top of it,
through where the gudgeon pin goes...

945
01:03:38.478 --> 01:03:39.876
and it'll make a great ash tray.

946
01:03:39.976 --> 01:03:41.874
Not that I approve of smoking,
mind you.

947
01:03:41.974 --> 01:03:43.971
- Thank you very much.
- Thanks a lot, mate. So long.

948
01:03:43.972 --> 01:03:47.268
- Sorry we couldn't fix your trailer.
- That's alright, I'll get there somehow.

949
01:03:47.868 --> 01:03:48.967
Burt?

950
01:03:49.266 --> 01:03:50.565
What?

951
01:03:50.865 --> 01:03:52.164
For the prostrate.

952
01:03:52.563 --> 01:03:54.361
Use with water,
plenty of water.

953
01:03:55.061 --> 01:03:56.859
It tastes bad. Really bad.

954
01:03:57.059 --> 01:03:58.557
Dogs balls huh?

955
01:03:59.057 --> 01:04:01.254
Well, thanks a lot mate.
See ya.

956
01:05:02.993 --> 01:05:03.892
Hello.

957
01:05:07.688 --> 01:05:09.087
Anyone home?

958
01:05:17.478 --> 01:05:18.277
Hello.

959
01:05:18.377 --> 01:05:19.676
Hello, there.

960
01:05:22.473 --> 01:05:25.770
I've got a spot of bother
with my trailer, lost a wheel.

961
01:05:27.668 --> 01:05:30.565
- You're not from around these parts.
- No, I'm from down there.

962
01:05:31.364 --> 01:05:33.762
- What?
- I'm from down under...

963
01:05:34.161 --> 01:05:36.259
The other side of the world,
New Zealand.

964
01:05:36.359 --> 01:05:38.157
Southern most city
in the British Empire.

965
01:05:38.557 --> 01:05:39.956
Called Invercargill.

966
01:05:40.155 --> 01:05:42.453
One of the most beautiful
cities on Earth.

967
01:05:43.152 --> 01:05:44.651
Name's Burt Munro.

968
01:05:44.851 --> 01:05:46.249
Burt? Ada.

969
01:05:46.449 --> 01:05:47.748
- What?
- Ada.

970
01:05:49.346 --> 01:05:50.445
There she is.

971
01:05:57.138 --> 01:05:59.236
We got some problems here,
yes sirree.

972
01:06:00.335 --> 01:06:02.233
I tell you what you need to do.

973
01:06:02.333 --> 01:06:05.830
Cannibalize the stuffed axel
out of that old Ford right there.

974
01:06:06.129 --> 01:06:08.027
Lucky for you
I've got some welding gear.

975
01:06:08.028 --> 01:06:10.225
- We'll get a new wheel on there pronto.
- Good.

976
01:06:19.816 --> 01:06:21.114
That's got it.

977
01:06:22.813 --> 01:06:24.211
When you are...

978
01:06:25.310 --> 01:06:26.309
finished there...

