01:06:27.009 --> 01:06:29.406
I've got something that
I want to show you.

980
01:06:29.806 --> 01:06:31.304
Yeah, what's that?

981
01:06:33.402 --> 01:06:34.801
Never you mind.

982
01:06:35.100 --> 01:06:36.799
You just get that wheel on
there right.

983
01:06:49.986 --> 01:06:51.684
Why'd you bring me out here?

984
01:06:51.884 --> 01:06:54.281
I want to show you this.

985
01:06:55.080 --> 01:06:56.079
What?

986
01:06:56.179 --> 01:06:57.278
Right here.

987
01:07:03.872 --> 01:07:08.167
I laid my old boy to rest
twelve years ago next week.

988
01:07:08.367 --> 01:07:09.966
I sure miss him.

989
01:07:10.165 --> 01:07:12.263
I sure do miss the old boy.

990
01:07:13.262 --> 01:07:14.861
He did his level best.

991
01:07:16.159 --> 01:07:17.458
He did.

992
01:07:17.858 --> 01:07:20.055
I always figured a man's
like a blade of grass...

993
01:07:20.255 --> 01:07:22.853
he grows up in the spring,
strong and healthy and green...

994
01:07:23.052 --> 01:07:27.648
and then he reaches middle age
and he ripens as it were and...

995
01:07:28.747 --> 01:07:31.744
in the autumn he,
like a blade of grass...

996
01:07:32.043 --> 01:07:35.340
he finishes just fades away
and he never comes back.

997
01:07:35.940 --> 01:07:37.938
Just like a blade of grass.

998
01:07:38.137 --> 01:07:40.935
I think when you're dead,
you're dead.

999
01:07:41.434 --> 01:07:44.231
I've always thought that,
since I grew up.

1000
01:07:44.531 --> 01:07:46.729
Is that your philosophy?

1001
01:07:46.929 --> 01:07:48.427
Well, I don't know,
yeah, I suppose it is...

1002
01:07:48.527 --> 01:07:53.322
when you get to my age these
thoughts cross your mind sometimes.

1003
01:07:54.821 --> 01:07:56.119
Jump!

1004
01:07:56.819 --> 01:07:58.217
Jump!

1005
01:07:58.817 --> 01:08:01.114
Sideways, you fool,
sideways!

1006
01:08:01.914 --> 01:08:04.611
My God, man, haven't you ever
seen a snake before?

1007
01:08:04.911 --> 01:08:06.509
No, we don't have snakes
in New Zealand.

1008
01:08:06.609 --> 01:08:08.707
Good God,
I ought to move there.

1009
01:08:09.606 --> 01:08:11.304
- Where's he going?
- Damn rattlers!

1010
01:08:11.904 --> 01:08:14.801
- Any more around here? Oh, God.
- Fancy this?

1011
01:08:15.100 --> 01:08:19.596
You come all this way
to bite the dust up at Boot Hill?

1012
01:08:21.394 --> 01:08:23.792
That would be a laugh,
wouldn't it?

1013
01:08:24.091 --> 01:08:25.490
Be a laugh.

1014
01:08:25.690 --> 01:08:26.889
There you go, there you go.

1015
01:08:28.387 --> 01:08:29.486
Oh, my God!

1016
01:08:36.079 --> 01:08:37.977
Where you gonna sleep tonight?

1017
01:08:39.776 --> 01:08:41.674
I don't know, I've no idea.

1018
01:08:44.471 --> 01:08:45.370
I don't know.

1019
01:09:05.550 --> 01:09:07.648
I had a strange dream
last night.

1020
01:09:09.945 --> 01:09:11.744
I dreamt about my late...

1021
01:09:13.042 --> 01:09:15.540
twin brother, Ernie.

1022
01:09:17.438 --> 01:09:20.835
I thought he was in the room here
looking down on us.

1023
01:09:22.932 --> 01:09:26.629
I guess it's all
that fun and games...

1024
01:09:26.630 --> 01:09:28.627
at the graveyard.

1025
01:09:31.724 --> 01:09:32.922
I suppose.

1026
01:09:33.222 --> 01:09:34.221
Oh, well.

1027
01:09:35.120 --> 01:09:39.016
Getting old ain't for the faint
of heart I'll tell you that.

1028
01:09:39.116 --> 01:09:41.614
Oh, God. What have you done
to my back, Ada?

1029
01:09:45.410 --> 01:09:46.809
I am getting old.

1030
01:09:48.807 --> 01:09:52.203
Come on old girl, make me a cup of tea,
I've got to hit the road.

1031
01:09:52.902 --> 01:09:56.199
Ada, come on, you haven't died
in our sleep, have you, old girl?

1032
01:09:56.499 --> 01:09:59.496
- Make me a cup of tea.
- Come here, lover boy.

1033
01:10:00.095 --> 01:10:01.694
I'll make it myself.

1034
01:10:02.193 --> 01:10:03.492
Thanks.

1035
01:10:07.488 --> 01:10:10.585
Now Burt, you promise me you're going
to pop in on your way back...

1036
01:10:10.785 --> 01:10:13.681
because I can always use
another little cuddle.

1037
01:10:13.682 --> 01:10:16.179
Yeah, that's what I said, Ada,
that's what I intend to do.

1038
01:10:16.379 --> 01:10:19.476
There's many good tune played on
an old Banjo as they say.

1039
01:10:19.875 --> 01:10:23.472
- And what we don't use, we lose.
- Well, that's what they say.

1040
01:10:24.471 --> 01:10:25.770
See ya. Ta ra, darling.

1041
01:10:26.269 --> 01:10:30.065
And you have good luck
with your Indian.

1042
01:10:30.265 --> 01:10:32.063
You should say
break a leg.

1043
01:10:33.762 --> 01:10:34.860
See ya.

1044
01:10:55.040 --> 01:10:56.039
Gidday.

1045
01:10:56.539 --> 01:10:58.037
Boy is it hot out there.

1046
01:10:59.935 --> 01:11:01.634
I bet the birds fly backwards
around here...

1047
01:11:01.734 --> 01:11:04.131
to keep the dust out
of their eyes.

1048
01:11:04.331 --> 01:11:07.927
- What can I get you?
- I'd like a cup of tea, please.

1049
01:11:08.227 --> 01:11:10.024
- Cup of tea?
- Yeah, best drink...

1050
01:11:10.025 --> 01:11:12.922
for quenching the thirst
when the weather's hot.

1051
01:11:13.322 --> 01:11:15.819
We haven't seen a cup of tea
in here ever.

1052
01:11:16.119 --> 01:11:20.015
We got Coors, we got Schlitz
or Miller or Coke and whiskey.

1053
01:11:22.213 --> 01:11:24.311
Well, I'll have coke then.

1054
01:11:28.806 --> 01:11:31.404
You know smoking's bad for you,
don't you?

1055
01:11:32.103 --> 01:11:34.001
- Is that so?
- Yeah.

1056
01:11:34.201 --> 01:11:36.599
Personally I don't smoke
and I don't drink.

1057
01:11:36.798 --> 01:11:38.996
I had the right education
from my dad on that one.

1058
01:11:39.196 --> 01:11:43.092
He was like King James the first,
great anti-smoking man.

1059
01:11:43.891 --> 01:11:46.389
Sounds like you're on a one
man crusade there grandpa.

1060
01:11:46.689 --> 01:11:49.985
Yeah, well, you're born with one
pair of lungs so why destroy...

1061
01:11:49.986 --> 01:11:51.584
them with that muck?

1062
01:11:52.583 --> 01:11:54.181
Where are you from?
Where's your home town?

1063
01:11:54.681 --> 01:11:56.679
- You English?
- Heavens no...

1064
01:11:56.878 --> 01:11:59.775
I'm no Pommie,
I'm from Invercargill in New Zealand.

1065
01:12:00.075 --> 01:12:02.173
- Where?
- Invercargill.

1066
01:12:02.473 --> 01:12:06.169
I-N-V-E-R-C-A-R-G-I-L-L.

1067
01:12:06.369 --> 01:12:10.265
I spell it with one L
sometimes to save ink.

1068
01:12:13.362 --> 01:12:17.558
- Got any of those critters over there?
- Oh yes, much bigger though...

1069
01:12:17.757 --> 01:12:20.155
we breed them down there
on big farms...

1070
01:12:20.655 --> 01:12:23.652
and we cut off their antlers and
send them over to Hong Kong and they...

1071
01:12:23.751 --> 01:12:27.348
grind the antlers into dust
and they eat that stuff...

1072
01:12:28.347 --> 01:12:31.344
must be some sort of aphrodisiac
or something.

1073
01:12:32.143 --> 01:12:33.941
Puts lead in your pencil.

1074
01:12:34.641 --> 01:12:37.238
You could do with some
of that, Leroy.

1075
01:12:40.235 --> 01:12:41.833
Your girlfriend?

1076
01:12:42.433 --> 01:12:43.432
Wife.

1077
01:12:45.130 --> 01:12:46.529
Oh, dear!

1078
01:12:52.423 --> 01:12:53.721
You alright?

1079
01:13:27.787 --> 01:13:30.784
Did you decide to leave Jackie
a tip after all?

1080
01:13:35.280 --> 01:13:38.177
Look sir, if you're not feeling well
you should drop in to the hospital...

1081
01:13:38.178 --> 01:13:39.376
in the next town.

1082
01:13:40.375 --> 01:13:41.574
Alright.

1083
01:14:19.735 --> 01:14:21.234
Roll down your window.

1084
01:14:21.434 --> 01:14:22.632
What?

1085
01:14:27.228 --> 01:14:28.427
What's the problem?

1086
01:14:28.626 --> 01:14:30.525
You're parked illegally.

1087
01:14:31.024 --> 01:14:34.021
- You're a danger to the passing traffic.
- Am I?

1088
01:14:34.620 --> 01:14:37.218
- Let's see your driver's license.
- Yeah, alright.

1089
01:14:39.815 --> 01:14:40.914
Here you are.

1090
01:14:48.007 --> 01:14:50.105
- Where are you from?
- From New Zealand.

1091
01:14:50.405 --> 01:14:54.301
That's the land of the
long white cloud. Aotearoa.

1092
01:14:54.700 --> 01:14:56.299
Home of the kiwi bird.

1093
01:14:56.598 --> 01:14:59.695
Well, I don't care if you're from Mars,
you cannot stop here.

1094
01:15:00.095 --> 01:15:01.093
Alright.

1095
01:15:01.094 --> 01:15:04.790
You cannot stop on the side of this road,
you're parked illegally.

1096
01:15:04.890 --> 01:15:09.386
Okay, well, sorry, I was having
a bit of a heart attack and...

1097
01:15:09.885 --> 01:15:11.783
well recovering
from one anyway.

1098
01:15:12.083 --> 01:15:14.481
Yeah, well, next time,
how about we stop at a proper rest area.

1099
01:15:14.680 --> 01:15:16.079
Yeah, alright, okay.

1100
01:15:16.379 --> 01:15:19.476
Name's Burt Munro.
Sorry about that.

1101
01:15:26.868 --> 01:15:28.367
Oil's OK.

1102
01:15:28.566 --> 01:15:30.165
- Thank you.
- That's alright, sir.

1103
01:15:30.664 --> 01:15:31.763
Excuse me.

1104
01:15:32.063 --> 01:15:33.362
- Hi, there.
- Hi.

1105
01:15:33.462 --> 01:15:36.858
Listen, I was wondering
if I could catch a ride?

1106
01:15:37.058 --> 01:15:40.954
My car, she just broke down and I'm
really trying to get to Salt Lake City.

1107
01:15:41.454 --> 01:15:44.151
I'm only going as far as Wendover,
that's where I'm stopping.

1108
01:15:44.351 --> 01:15:46.448
Well, anything would be
better than nothing.

1109
01:15:46.449 --> 01:15:49.545
- Ain't that the truth? Hop in, mate.
- Hey, thank you.

1110
01:15:51.444 --> 01:15:54.041
I'm going to go see
my girlfriend...

1111
01:15:54.241 --> 01:15:56.439
she just moved from LA
to Salt Lake, so.

1112
01:15:57.438 --> 01:15:59.635
I'm home on leave from 'Nam.

1113
01:15:59.935 --> 01:16:01.334
- What?
- Vietnam?

1114
01:16:01.533 --> 01:16:02.732
Oh, yeah.

1115
01:16:03.232 --> 01:16:05.829
Hey, what is that you've
got strapped on back there?

1116
01:16:06.229 --> 01:16:09.525
That, young fellow,
is an Indian.

1117
01:16:11.024 --> 01:16:12.023
Motorcycle.

1118
01:16:13.222 --> 01:16:15.020
So what are you doing
in Vietnam?

1119
01:16:15.120 --> 01:16:17.018
I'm involved
in operation ranch hand.

1120
01:16:17.318 --> 01:16:19.815
Oh, what's that?
Farming or something?

1121
01:16:20.215 --> 01:16:23.012
No, not exactly,
we just started this program...

1122
01:16:23.412 --> 01:16:27.108
we are spraying the jungle
from the air with herbicides...

1123
01:16:27.308 --> 01:16:30.504
so the enemy, the Vietcong,
don't have any place to hide.

1124
01:16:30.904 --> 01:16:35.100
Agent Orange we call this stuff,
it comes in these big old orange drums.

1125
01:16:37.098 --> 01:16:38.996
How is it working out?

1126
01:16:40.095 --> 01:16:44.191
Well, I'm home on two months leave
and I've got to get my arse back there.

1127
01:16:44.391 --> 01:16:48.486
We should have this war done in 6 months
or so, that's what they keep telling us.

1128
01:16:48.686 --> 01:16:51.084
Can't wait to get my arse out of there
to tell you the truth.

1129
01:16:51.384 --> 01:16:54.880
Yeah, I remember
the Great War in 1914...

1130
01:16:55.180 --> 01:16:59.475
I was about your age and
that's what they kept telling everyone.

1131
01:17:00.375 --> 01:17:02.273
Soon be over.

1132
01:17:02.572 --> 01:17:05.669
20 million dead and four years later
it was still going on.

1133
01:17:06.768 --> 01:17:09.266
Not as bad
as the big flu epidemic though.

1134
01:17:09.965 --> 01:17:12.962
Killed 21 million, that did.
Maybe more.

1135
01:17:13.861 --> 01:17:15.759
Every day,
when I left to go to work...

1136
01:17:15.859 --> 01:17:19.156
my mum would spray some formalin
on my shirt...

1137
01:17:20.255 --> 01:17:22.852
and maybe that's why
I didn't catch it.

1138
01:17:23.451 --> 01:17:26.149
Or maybe I was just lucky.
You never know.

1139
01:17:28.347 --> 01:17:30.345
- Knock on wood.
- Yep.

1140
01:17:32.442 --> 01:17:34.240
You know,
life's a funny thing...

1141
01:17:34.241 --> 01:17:36.538
you never know
what's around the corner, do you?

1142
01:17:38.936 --> 01:17:40.434
Your shaving brush.

1143
01:17:41.433 --> 01:17:42.632
Has had it's day.

1144
01:17:43.032 --> 01:17:44.930
It won't achieve.

1145
01:17:45.729 --> 01:17:47.328
The Modern way.

1146
01:17:49.226 --> 01:17:51.024
Burma Shave.

1147
01:17:52.822 --> 01:17:56.019
She doesn't kiss ya
like she used to?

1148
01:17:56.418 --> 01:17:59.515
Has she seen
some smoother rooster?

1149
01:18:00.514 --> 01:18:02.013
Burma Shave.

1150
01:18:02.512 --> 01:18:05.709
These signs we dedicate...

1151
01:18:06.309 --> 01:18:07.507
to men...

1152
01:18:07.707 --> 01:18:10.504
who've had no date of late.

1153
01:18:11.104 --> 01:18:12.602
Burma Shave.

1154
01:18:13.202 --> 01:18:16.099
Yeah, that's us.
Well, you anyway.

1155
01:18:22.592 --> 01:18:24.191
Look at that.

1156
01:18:24.590 --> 01:18:26.788
That's a cowboy and a half.

1157
01:18:29.385 --> 01:18:31.383
I was thinking I'd come out
to the Salt with you.

1158
01:18:31.483 --> 01:18:33.481
I'd like to be there
the first time you see it...

1159
01:18:33.482 --> 01:18:35.280
it's only a couple of miles
up the road so.

1160
01:18:35.280 --> 01:18:37.178
Yeah, alright then,
that sounds good.

1161
01:18:37.477 --> 01:18:39.975
Looks like there's a lot of people
in town for speed week, huh?

1162
01:18:40.275 --> 01:18:41.673
Yeah, looks like it.

1163
01:18:44.470 --> 01:18:47.767
This is it, Burt.
We're gonna take a left right up here.

1164
01:19:00.055 --> 01:19:01.553
Bonneville...

1165
01:19:02.053 --> 01:19:03.551
I mean I can't believe it.

1166
01:19:03.851 --> 01:19:06.149
I mean I'm here, I've made it.

1167
01:19:07.547 --> 01:19:08.846
I've made it.

1168
01:19:36.818 --> 01:19:39.715
You know, all my life
I wanted to do something big.

1169
01:19:40.814 --> 01:19:43.311
Something better and bigger
than all the other jokers.

1170
01:19:45.210 --> 01:19:46.708
This is it, Bonneville.

1171
01:19:47.907 --> 01:19:51.603
This is the place
where big things happen.

1172
01:19:55.100 --> 01:19:58.896
Do you realize, Rusty, the fastest
man has ever gone on land is here?

1173
01:20:00.095 --> 01:20:01.793
Right here, where we are now.

1174
01:20:05.389 --> 01:20:08.786
Malcolm Campbell did it here,
with a Bluebird.

1175
01:20:09.685 --> 01:20:11.783
First guy to go
over 300 mile an hour...

1176
01:20:11.883 --> 01:20:14.880
and then later his son, Donald Campbell
was here with Proteus.

1177
01:20:14.980 --> 01:20:18.776
He crashed at 350 mile an hour
and lived to tell the tale.

1178
01:20:20.674 --> 01:20:22.173
John Cobb was here.

1179
01:20:23.271 --> 01:20:26.268
First guy
to go over 400 mile an hour.

1180
01:20:27.267 --> 01:20:29.265
All the great attempts.

1181
01:20:29.765 --> 01:20:32.562
George Easton with Thunderbolt and...

1182
01:20:33.062 --> 01:20:36.059
Mickey Thompson
with Challenger.

1183
01:20:39.355 --> 01:20:42.053
I'm telling you, Rusty,
this place is holy ground, mate.

1184
01:20:43.451 --> 01:20:44.650
Holy ground.

1185
01:20:46.149 --> 01:20:48.246
And I made it here.

1186
01:21:17.517 --> 01:21:18.716
Well, Burt.

1187
01:21:19.315 --> 01:21:20.414
Thanks a million.

1188
01:21:20.714 --> 01:21:22.013
I'll be looking for you
in the record books.

1189
01:21:22.113 --> 01:21:24.510
You take care out there in Vietnam,
won't you?

1190
01:21:24.511 --> 01:21:25.509
I'll be trying.

1191
01:21:26.009 --> 01:21:27.307
- Okay, mate.
- Drive safe.

1192
01:21:27.607 --> 01:21:29.106
- See ya
- See ya.

1193
01:22:46.928 --> 01:22:48.027
God.

1194
01:23:16.098 --> 01:23:17.497
Jesus.

1195
01:23:50.264 --> 01:23:51.863
- Gidday.
- Hey, there.

1196
01:23:54.860 --> 01:23:56.758
- It's going to be a great day.
- Yeah.

1197
01:23:57.257 --> 01:23:59.755
Still... no wind.

1198
01:24:00.454 --> 01:24:02.052
Lovely day for a run.

1199
01:24:03.851 --> 01:24:05.599
Salt's in good shape.

1200
01:24:05.600 --> 01:24:07.347
Yeah. Firm and dry.

1201
01:24:07.647 --> 01:24:09.845
Dead flat. No soft patches.

1202
01:24:10.444 --> 01:24:12.142
Not like the beach.

1203
01:24:13.241 --> 01:24:15.139
I can do it here.

1204
01:24:15.739 --> 01:24:16.838
Yep.

1205
01:24:17.437 --> 01:24:19.735
This week.
It's what we're here for.

1206
01:24:24.430 --> 01:24:25.529
Wow, is that yours?

1207
01:24:26.628 --> 01:24:27.527
Yep.

1208
01:24:28.426 --> 01:24:30.224
Gosh, she's a beauty.

1209
01:24:31.223 --> 01:24:33.221
I bet she goes fast.

1210
01:24:34.120 --> 01:24:36.518
- That yours?
- Yeah, that's an old Indian.

1211
01:24:37.217 --> 01:24:39.015
My name's Munro, Burt Munro.

1212
01:24:39.215 --> 01:24:42.112
- From down under, New Zealand.
- A long way from home.

1213
01:24:42.312 --> 01:24:44.810
Jim Moffatt, San Jose,
California.

1214
01:24:45.009 --> 01:24:46.808
- Nice to meet you, Burt.
- Good to meet you, Jim.

1215
01:24:47.007 --> 01:24:48.806
<i>Let's get to the start line.</i>

1216
01:24:49.105 --> 01:24:53.701
<i>The race is about to start
and all the racers are excited.</i>

1217
01:24:54.100 --> 01:24:58.096
This car is driven by Jim Moffatt,
San Jose, California.

1218
01:24:58.396 --> 01:25:01.793
The other pilots are...

1219
01:25:12.282 --> 01:25:14.780
- Come on, guys, 15 minutes.
- Come on.

1220
01:25:15.279 --> 01:25:16.977
Come on, let's go.

1221
01:25:25.469 --> 01:25:27.467
- Morning.
- Hello, Burt Munro.

1222
01:25:27.767 --> 01:25:29.165
- Mike.
- Hi, Mike.

1223
01:25:30.164 --> 01:25:32.562
- Are you checked in?
- No, not yet.

1224
01:25:33.561 --> 01:25:37.357
Well, you've got to remove the shell
before we do the tech inspection.

1225
01:25:37.557 --> 01:25:39.855
- Where do I check in?
- It's just over there.

1226
01:25:40.054 --> 01:25:41.952
- Thanks, fellas.
- Okay.

1227
01:25:44.350 --> 01:25:45.549
I gotta see this.

1228
01:25:45.849 --> 01:25:49.445
Hello, I've come to check in.
Munro, Burt Munro.

1229
01:25:49.745 --> 01:25:51.343
Registration number?

1230
01:25:52.142 --> 01:25:53.341
What?

1231
01:25:53.541 --> 01:25:56.438
Registration number.
I don't see your number here.

1232
01:25:56.638 --> 01:25:59.535
No, it's number 35.

1233
01:25:59.735 --> 01:26:03.631
It's on the side of my motorcycle
over there, that's my lucky number.

1234
01:26:03.930 --> 01:26:05.229
Have you registered?

1235
01:26:06.828 --> 01:26:09.324
No, that's what
I've come over for.

1236
01:26:09.325 --> 01:26:11.623
These two blokes sent me over here,
Mike and someone else.

1237
01:26:11.922 --> 01:26:14.320
Sir, registration closed
last month.

1238
01:26:14.520 --> 01:26:17.916
If you haven't registered,
I'm sorry, you just can't run.

1239
01:26:20.814 --> 01:26:22.512
I can't run?

1240
01:26:23.910 --> 01:26:27.107
Well, how was I supposed to know
I should have pre-registered?

1241
01:26:27.108 --> 01:26:29.305
I've come a heck of a long way
to ride my bike.

1242
01:26:29.306 --> 01:26:31.502
I'm not going anywhere
until I've done just that.

1243
01:26:31.503 --> 01:26:34.400
I've come all the way from New Zealand,
you know. It's a long way.

1244
01:26:34.800 --> 01:26:36.398
Look, mister,
we don't make the rules.

1245
01:26:36.698 --> 01:26:40.094
An event like this doesn't just happen
in one day, rules are rules.

1246
01:26:40.095 --> 01:26:42.091
Entries closed July 31st.

1247
01:26:42.092 --> 01:26:45.888
Well, crikey, I live in Invercargill,
it's half way round the bloody earth.

1248
01:26:46.388 --> 01:26:49.085
How was I supposed to know these things?
I didn't know all this stuff.

1249
01:26:49.086 --> 01:26:50.384
Sir, it's not our problem.

1250
01:26:50.484 --> 01:26:53.081
I thought I could just turn up here
and have my bike timed.

1251
01:26:53.082 --> 01:26:55.679
- You don't have to call me sir...
- Well, you thought wrong.

1252
01:27:05.369 --> 01:27:07.467
Jim Moffatt!

1253
01:27:07.966 --> 01:27:10.264
It's Burt, Burt Munro.
Can you come over here, mate?

1254
01:27:11.063 --> 01:27:12.362
I'll be right back.

1255
01:27:13.161 --> 01:27:14.760
I need a bit of help.

1256
01:27:15.059 --> 01:27:16.558
Hey, Burt. What's up?

1257
01:27:16.957 --> 01:27:20.654
Well, I have these blokes telling
me I can't run my bike...

1258
01:27:20.853 --> 01:27:22.851
because I'm not pre-registered.

1259
01:27:23.151 --> 01:27:25.649
- You didn't register?
- No, I didn't know anything about it.

1260
01:27:25.749 --> 01:27:28.246
You know how it is Jim,
rules are rules.

1261
01:27:28.546 --> 01:27:31.643
- You should have registered months ago.
- I didn't know.

1262
01:27:33.141 --> 01:27:35.639
I'll have a talk with these guys later,
see if I can change their minds.

1263
01:27:35.838 --> 01:27:39.235
- Your blood's worth bottling.
- I don't know about that.

1264
01:27:39.435 --> 01:27:41.432
Look,
we can talk about this later.

1265
01:27:41.433 --> 01:27:43.231
Maybe you can let him go
through tech inspection.

1266
01:27:43.431 --> 01:27:46.827
Get that out of the way?
Just in case we can let him ride.

1267
01:27:47.727 --> 01:27:49.525
You're asking a lot.

1268
01:27:50.724 --> 01:27:51.822
Alright.

1269
01:27:55.818 --> 01:27:57.317
- Okay.
- Alright.

1270
01:27:57.617 --> 01:27:59.715
- Make me proud.
- Thanks a lot.

1271
01:28:00.014 --> 01:28:02.012
You give me a bit
of a fright there.

1272
01:28:06.807 --> 01:28:09.705
You know these don't look
like high speed tyres.

1273
01:28:10.004 --> 01:28:11.603
Well, they are high speed tyres.

1274
01:28:12.402 --> 01:28:15.699
Look at these hairline cracks,
these tyres have got to be 25 years old.

1275
01:28:16.098 --> 01:28:17.796
- What happened to the tread?
- What?

1276
01:28:17.996 --> 01:28:20.093
I said,
what happened to the tread?

1277
01:28:20.094 --> 01:28:21.493
Well, I cut it off,
that's what happened to the tread...

1278
01:28:21.593 --> 01:28:22.990
I cut it off with a carving knife...

1279
01:28:22.991 --> 01:28:25.389
otherwise it wouldn't be
a high speed tyre, would it?

1280
01:28:25.788 --> 01:28:27.186
What are you talking about?

1281
01:28:27.187 --> 01:28:30.384
Well, you've got to keep the weight in
otherwise when you get to a high speed...

1282
01:28:30.385 --> 01:28:32.682
the centrifugal force will
the tread right off, wouldn't it?

1283
01:28:33.081 --> 01:28:36.977
I run them on 65 pounds of air and
that tyre's safe up to 300 miles an hour.

1284
01:28:37.177 --> 01:28:39.575
I guarantee it. These are high
speed tyres and I made them.

1285
01:28:39.774 --> 01:28:41.673
Well, you're going to have
to replace them.

1286
01:28:41.972 --> 01:28:43.571
The suspension here is
a leaf spring...

1287
01:28:43.870 --> 01:28:44.969
I mean can we pass that?

1288
01:28:45.269 --> 01:28:48.266
Geez, last leaf spring on a motorcycle
must have been in the 1920s.

1289
01:28:48.566 --> 01:28:49.864
Well, it is 42 years old.

1290
01:28:50.164 --> 01:28:54.060
- These brakes look completely inadequate.
- Well, I'm planning on going, not stopping.

1291
01:28:54.160 --> 01:28:57.057
Well, the brakes were old
fashioned 40 years ago.

1292
01:28:57.756 --> 01:28:59.555
Is this a hinge of a gate post?

1293
01:28:59.754 --> 01:29:01.852
No, that's from an old kitchen door.

1294
01:29:03.750 --> 01:29:07.447
Let me just ask you what is this?

1295
01:29:07.647 --> 01:29:10.644
It's a cork, what does it look like?
It's a cork from a brandy bottle.

1296
01:29:10.843 --> 01:29:15.239
You know, the thing is it's all about
weight. The less weight, the faster you go.

1297
01:29:15.339 --> 01:29:16.438
And where's your chute?

1298
01:29:16.638 --> 01:29:18.536
- What?
- Where's your parachute?

1299
01:29:18.636 --> 01:29:20.534
I'm not planning on bailing out.

1300
01:29:20.634 --> 01:29:23.031
No wait,
you've got to have a safety chute.

1301
01:29:23.032 --> 01:29:24.529
Well, I can't afford one.

1302
01:29:24.530 --> 01:29:27.227
These forks, if they give out we've
got ourselves some real problems.

1303
01:29:27.427 --> 01:29:29.724
I think I'd have a bit of
a problem that way, wouldn't I?

1304
01:29:30.424 --> 01:29:31.922
- Where's your fire suit?
- What?

1305
01:29:32.222 --> 01:29:33.620
Where's your fire suit?

1306
01:29:33.621 --> 01:29:36.018
Good heavens, man,
I don't intend to burst into flames.

1307
01:29:36.218 --> 01:29:38.366
Always wear me old suit pants
for good luck.

1308
01:29:38.367 --> 01:29:40.513
If they were good enough
to get married in...

1309
01:29:40.514 --> 01:29:42.811
they're good enough to ride
this old girl in and no...

1310
01:29:43.111 --> 01:29:45.209
I tuck the legs of my pants
into my socks like this...

1311
01:29:45.409 --> 01:29:48.506
stop them getting caught
in the chain and Bob's your uncle.

1312
01:29:48.905 --> 01:29:51.203
You've got your suit pants,
what are you gonna wear on top?

1313
01:29:51.204 --> 01:29:52.002
What?

1314
01:29:52.102 --> 01:29:55.099
You've got your suit pants,
what do you intend to wear on top?

1315
01:29:55.299 --> 01:29:59.694
Yes, a black woollen shirt, New Zealand
wool, water resistant, fire resistant...

1316
01:29:59.794 --> 01:30:01.393
and me bash hat.

1317
01:30:02.092 --> 01:30:03.591
Bash hat?

1318
01:30:04.290 --> 01:30:05.288
Yeah, crash helmet.

1319
01:30:05.289 --> 01:30:08.586
You're crazy, you've got to wear
at least a leather jacket on top.

1320
01:30:08.586 --> 01:30:11.882
You put the bike down on the salt,
it's like coarse sand paper...

1321
01:30:11.883 --> 01:30:13.281
it's going to rub
your head right off.

1322
01:30:13.282 --> 01:30:15.078
I couldn't get into the shell...

1323
01:30:15.079 --> 01:30:18.176
with anything bulkier than the shirt on
my back. It's a very tight fit in there.

1324
01:30:18.376 --> 01:30:19.475
Straight out of the ark.

1325
01:30:20.574 --> 01:30:22.572
- What did you say?
- Straight out of the ark.

1326
01:30:22.771 --> 01:30:25.668
Don't be so cheeky.
What's your name, young man?

1327
01:30:26.268 --> 01:30:28.166
McFarlane. Mike McFarlane.

1328
01:30:28.366 --> 01:30:31.463
I knew a McFarlane, he used to sell
milking machines in Timaru.

1329
01:30:31.662 --> 01:30:34.060
You must be related to him
because he was a total prick.

1330
01:30:35.259 --> 01:30:37.357
Look here, you don't even have
a fire extinguisher installed.

1331
01:30:37.557 --> 01:30:42.152
Mike McFarlane used to give me milking
machine parts to make my sprockets with.

1332
01:30:42.252 --> 01:30:43.350
How old are you?

1333
01:30:43.351 --> 01:30:45.049
I don't know,
he was about 35 when I knew him.

1334
01:30:45.249 --> 01:30:46.447
No how old are you?

1335
01:30:46.448 --> 01:30:49.844
His brother owned a general store
down in a place called Bulls...

1336
01:30:50.144 --> 01:30:52.741
- that's a town in New Zealand.
- Sir, your machine is not safe.

1337
01:30:53.141 --> 01:30:55.938
I've been doing this for 43 years
and I'm still here to tell the tale.

1338
01:30:56.138 --> 01:30:59.335
Time's change, we started taking
airplanes instead of riding horseback.

1339
01:30:59.535 --> 01:31:01.433
- Horse power?
- Horse back. Horse back.

1340
01:31:01.434 --> 01:31:02.731
Horse back, yeah.
I got you, yeah.

1341
01:31:03.730 --> 01:31:05.029
You're too old.

1342
01:31:05.429 --> 01:31:08.326
Bollocks. I may have this saggy skin
on the outside...

1343
01:31:08.327 --> 01:31:09.824
but on the inside
I'm still 18 years old...

1344
01:31:10.024 --> 01:31:12.022
and I'll give you a run for your money,
young fella.

1345
01:31:13.521 --> 01:31:15.119
You need some help?

1346
01:31:15.419 --> 01:31:16.518
Hello.

1347
01:31:17.616 --> 01:31:20.514
Rollie Free, Marty Dickerson,
we're a couple of bike fans.

1348
01:31:20.813 --> 01:31:23.710
- Burt Munro from Kiwi land.
- Pleasure, Burt.

1349
01:31:26.108 --> 01:31:27.906
You got me good there.

1350
01:31:28.106 --> 01:31:29.604
Where are you staying?

1351
01:31:29.804 --> 01:31:31.801
That's my salubrious
accommodation...

1352
01:31:31.802 --> 01:31:34.000
I usually sleep at night
in the back seat.

1353
01:31:34.300 --> 01:31:35.898
Salubrious you say Munro, huh?

1354
01:31:37.097 --> 01:31:38.895
We've been hearing a lot about you.

1355
01:31:39.095 --> 01:31:41.193
Sounds like you're cutting
your finances mighty fine.

1356
01:31:41.493 --> 01:31:42.991
Yeah, you could say that again.

1357
01:31:43.191 --> 01:31:45.389
We'll we're up at the Western Ridge,
why don't you drop by...

1358
01:31:45.588 --> 01:31:47.586
it looks as though you could
use a good shower...

1359
01:31:47.686 --> 01:31:50.683
and everybody's staying there and
I bet that there's a spare bed there too.

1360
01:31:50.983 --> 01:31:53.381
Thanks a lot, you yanks
are classic you know that?

1361
01:31:53.580 --> 01:31:55.479
You don't catch me that easily.

1362
01:32:01.473 --> 01:32:02.771
Hey, Burt.

1363
01:32:03.071 --> 01:32:04.270
Hello.

1364
01:32:06.368 --> 01:32:08.266
The front forks could
go at any time...

1365
01:32:08.366 --> 01:32:10.663
the suspension is right out
of the 1920s.

1366
01:32:10.863 --> 01:32:13.161
Got hairline cracks all
over his tyres...

1367
01:32:13.261 --> 01:32:16.158
he's got no fire extinguisher,
no safety chute.

1368
01:32:16.358 --> 01:32:19.754
I told you, if it's a time problem, the
old guy's welcome to use some of my time.

1369
01:32:19.954 --> 01:32:22.252
It's not a time problem,
it's a bike problem.

1370
01:32:22.551 --> 01:32:23.950
Well, I think we ought
to let him run.

1371
01:32:24.549 --> 01:32:26.547
He came all the way from
New Zealand to do this.

1372
01:32:26.747 --> 01:32:29.245
Jim, have you had a good look
at his machine?

1373
01:32:29.345 --> 01:32:31.143
All I know is the man's
the genuine article.

1374
01:32:31.443 --> 01:32:33.441
Yeah, but the bike is
the genuine dinosaur.

1375
01:32:33.740 --> 01:32:36.636
Look, we carry the cans
for the decisions around here.

1376
01:32:36.637 --> 01:32:39.634
And if he kills himself and there's
about a 100 to 1 that he will...

1377
01:32:39.635 --> 01:32:42.332
...we are gonna have a hell
of a lot of trouble on our hands.

1378
01:32:42.432 --> 01:32:47.127
Yeah, sounds like we're a bunch
of chicken shits if you want my opinion.

1379
01:32:47.227 --> 01:32:50.923
His bike didn't even come close
to passing tech inspection, Jim.

1380
01:33:00.713 --> 01:33:01.413
Burt.

1381
01:33:02.312 --> 01:33:03.710
Hello, Jim. Come in.

1382
01:33:04.310 --> 01:33:06.207
Rollie Free said
I could find you here.

1383
01:33:06.208 --> 01:33:09.205
Rollie Free, he's the best,
he's a real gentleman.

1384
01:33:09.405 --> 01:33:11.802
He set me up in this place
for nothing.

1385
01:33:15.299 --> 01:33:16.398
What are you doing?

1386
01:33:16.897 --> 01:33:20.294
Well, the soft shoe polish
fills in the cracks makes the tyres...

1387
01:33:20.493 --> 01:33:22.691
Look spick and span,
good as new.

1388
01:33:22.891 --> 01:33:24.390
Cheaper than new ones anyway.

1389
01:33:24.689 --> 01:33:25.888
I didn't see that.

1390
01:33:28.585 --> 01:33:30.583
Well? Can I run?

1391
01:33:33.381 --> 01:33:34.679
I'm sorry, Burt.

1392
01:33:41.872 --> 01:33:43.970
Who the heck
do they think they are?

1393
01:33:44.769 --> 01:33:48.266
Crikey Jim, you know, I'm not trying
to run a mile in four minutes...

1394
01:33:48.366 --> 01:33:51.163
all I've got to do is sit there
and open up the throttle...

1395
01:33:51.263 --> 01:33:54.659
I mean, after all
it's my ruddy life, isn't it?

1396
01:33:55.658 --> 01:33:57.256
Can't you do anything?

1397
01:33:57.257 --> 01:34:01.852
I mean, I just want to try and get her
to go over 200 just once that's all...

1398
01:34:01.952 --> 01:34:03.849
once I've cracked 200
I'll be quite happy...

1399
01:34:03.850 --> 01:34:06.447
to piss off back home to New Zealand
and Bob's your uncle.

1400
01:34:07.047 --> 01:34:11.043
You're a well respected man around here,
can you talk to them?

1401
01:34:11.343 --> 01:34:12.541
I tried.

1402
01:34:13.341 --> 01:34:16.338
You've got as much chance
of writing yourself off as I have...

1403
01:34:16.338 --> 01:34:19.135
you know that.
Just talk to them again.

1404
01:34:20.433 --> 01:34:22.631
I know they'll listen to you, mate.

1405
01:34:25.029 --> 01:34:27.826
Okay Burt, I'll try.
See you tomorrow.

1406
01:34:28.126 --> 01:34:29.225
Okay.

1407
01:34:32.322 --> 01:34:36.018
I mean I'm half the age of some
of those characters out there.

1408
01:34:41.912 --> 01:34:43.311
What's that?

1409
01:34:43.610 --> 01:34:45.309
That's just indigestion.

1410
01:34:51.003 --> 01:34:55.898
Everyone wants us old buggers
to curl up in some quiet corner and die.

1411
01:34:56.797 --> 01:35:00.593
Well, Burt Munro's not ready to finish
yet, I'll tell you that, mate.

1412
01:35:03.291 --> 01:35:05.688
I'll give it a shot
but I'm not promising anything.

1413
01:35:06.387 --> 01:35:08.286
Thanks, mate.
Thanks a lot.

1414
01:35:13.680 --> 01:35:16.577
<i>The famous Challenger One...</i>

1415
01:35:26.567 --> 01:35:28.266
What is he doing?

1416
01:35:28.565 --> 01:35:30.963
- Didn't Jim tell him?
- He says he did.

1417
01:35:31.462 --> 01:35:34.260
- Well, then what's he doing here?
- Why won't you let him run?

1418
01:35:34.260 --> 01:35:36.757
Hey, he's too old
and his bike's too old.

1419
01:35:37.057 --> 01:35:39.255
He's come half way round the world
to ride that cycle.

1420
01:35:39.554 --> 01:35:40.753
Yeah, come on.

1421
01:35:41.053 --> 01:35:45.049
- Wendy, if he was to kill himself.
- So? It's his life.

1422
01:35:45.948 --> 01:35:47.646
Keep an eye out
for those officials.

1423
01:35:47.746 --> 01:35:50.393
You sure you want to do this?
I'm not sure it's a good idea.

1424
01:35:50.394 --> 01:35:53.041
Hurry up. If we're going to do
this thing you've got to hurry.

1425
01:35:53.141 --> 01:35:55.139
Alright, let's go,
here's your helmet.

1426
01:35:57.137 --> 01:35:58.435
Here's your goggles.

1427
01:35:58.735 --> 01:36:00.633
- Come on, Burt. We've got to go.
- Yeah, right.

1428
01:36:00.733 --> 01:36:02.331
Come on, put them on.

1429
01:36:07.127 --> 01:36:08.325
Go, go, come on.

1430
01:36:12.621 --> 01:36:13.920
Okay, let's go, push.

1431
01:36:14.519 --> 01:36:15.918
Push, go fast.

1432
01:36:16.218 --> 01:36:17.416
Hey, you can't. Hey...

1433
01:36:18.016 --> 01:36:20.114
- you can't do that.
- Come on, come on!

1434
01:36:21.712 --> 01:36:23.011
Hang on!

1435
01:36:27.706 --> 01:36:29.304
Hey, where are you going with that?

1436
01:36:34.599 --> 01:36:36.597
Stop, stop, stop, stop.

1437
01:36:37.496 --> 01:36:40.593
What the hell are you doing, Burt?
What the hell are you doing?

1438
01:36:40.993 --> 01:36:42.890
Just getting her warmed up, Bob.

1439
01:36:42.891 --> 01:36:44.389
Didn't look like you were
getting her warmed up.

1440
01:36:44.589 --> 01:36:46.887
Jesus, he was going to take
the thing for a freakin' run.

1441
01:36:46.888 --> 01:36:47.986
Bob.

1442
01:36:47.987 --> 01:36:49.085
Oh, boy.

1443
01:36:51.183 --> 01:36:54.779
That is the most determined man
I have ever seen in my entire life.

1444
01:36:55.478 --> 01:36:57.376
I kind of feel sorry
for the old cooty.

1445
01:36:58.975 --> 01:37:00.473
Coming all this way.

1446
01:37:00.973 --> 01:37:03.121
Isn't there some way
we can accommodate him?

1447
01:37:03.122 --> 01:37:05.268
I mean there can't be
much risk there...

1448
01:37:05.368 --> 01:37:08.265
his bike will be
lucky if it does 70.

1449
01:37:08.465 --> 01:37:11.762
What do you say? What if we bend
the rules this once, huh?

1450
01:37:14.259 --> 01:37:15.258
Jesus!

1451
01:37:18.455 --> 01:37:20.054
Bob and I had a little chat...

1452
01:37:20.253 --> 01:37:23.550
and we're thinking we're gonna
organize a handling run for you.

1453
01:37:24.449 --> 01:37:27.246
- You are? What?
- A handling run.

1454
01:37:27.646 --> 01:37:29.944
All the officials,
we're gonna get into our vehicles and...

1455
01:37:29.945 --> 01:37:31.142
- You're joking, huh?
- No, I'm not.

1456
01:37:31.143 --> 01:37:33.239
We're going to follow
along behind you...

1457
01:37:33.240 --> 01:37:35.238
and we're going to see
if you're okay to ride this beast.

1458
01:37:35.239 --> 01:37:36.336
Of course I'm okay to ride it.

1459
01:37:36.337 --> 01:37:39.534
First thing tomorrow morning, alright?
Bright and early.

1460
01:37:41.532 --> 01:37:42.831
Well, thanks fellas.

1461
01:37:43.830 --> 01:37:45.928
Hey. My luck's in then.

1462
01:37:48.725 --> 01:37:50.523
- You alright?
- Yeah.

1463
01:37:50.623 --> 01:37:52.022
Don't hurt yourself.

1464
01:38:03.610 --> 01:38:06.907
Okay, everyone listen up.
This is what we're gonna do.

1465
01:38:07.306 --> 01:38:09.704
Burt, you're gonna get rolling...

1466
01:38:09.804 --> 01:38:13.600
ride slowly along. We'll all jump in
our vehicles, follow you down the track.

1467
01:38:13.601 --> 01:38:15.998
- See if you can handle this thing.
- I'll handle her alright.

1468
01:38:16.297 --> 01:38:17.896
Alright. Everybody got that?

1469
01:38:18.195 --> 01:38:20.693
Okay, everybody,
let's get in the cars.

1470
01:38:44.469 --> 01:38:46.767
Hope that old man doesn't make
a fool of himself.

1471
01:38:51.962 --> 01:38:53.061
Here we go.

1472
01:38:53.960 --> 01:38:55.558
I'm ready, let's go.

1473
01:38:56.157 --> 01:38:57.156
Push it!

1474
01:38:57.556 --> 01:38:59.055
Faster, boys.

1475
01:39:01.152 --> 01:39:02.351
Go, Burt!

1476
01:39:26.827 --> 01:39:27.926
Sixty.

1477
01:39:28.525 --> 01:39:30.024
Sixty-five, seventy.

1478
01:39:31.722 --> 01:39:32.921
That a boy, Burt.

1479
01:39:33.120 --> 01:39:34.119
Seventy-five.

1480
01:39:34.819 --> 01:39:37.616
There he goes up to eighty,
eighty, eighty five.

1481
01:39:42.211 --> 01:39:43.110
Ninety.

1482
01:39:50.503 --> 01:39:53.100
Ninety-five,
look at that thing go.

1483
01:40:03.890 --> 01:40:06.587
- Holy smoke.
- He's leaving them behind!

1484
01:40:06.887 --> 01:40:08.684
What the hell is
that old guy up to?

1485
01:40:08.685 --> 01:40:10.483
Nobody told him
he could give it everything.

1486
01:40:10.683 --> 01:40:13.080
I guess that solves the question
of whether or not he can handle it.

1487
01:40:13.280 --> 01:40:15.478
We were doing ninety-five
and he left us in the dust.

1488
01:40:15.678 --> 01:40:17.076
Look at him go!

1489
01:40:17.276 --> 01:40:18.475
That a boy, go, Burt.

1490
01:40:57.836 --> 01:40:59.734
Hold her firm.

1491
01:40:59.934 --> 01:41:01.032
Hold her firm.

1492
01:41:01.332 --> 01:41:03.330
Got it? Don't let it go.

1493
01:41:04.729 --> 01:41:06.227
That was a disaster!

1494
01:41:07.226 --> 01:41:10.223
- Hey, Burt. How'd it go.
- Not good.

1495
01:41:14.719 --> 01:41:16.217
So, what's the verdict?

1496
01:41:16.517 --> 01:41:19.414
When you opened up there in top
gear you sure left us in the dust.

1497
01:41:19.514 --> 01:41:22.011
I couldn't even get her out
of second gear, Earl.

1498
01:41:22.411 --> 01:41:26.307
The plugs were oiling up, I had to feed
her more juice up the revs a little.

1499
01:41:26.507 --> 01:41:29.504
Well, I guess we'll see if you're
telling us the truth, Munro.

1500
01:41:31.402 --> 01:41:34.499
Are you telling me I can officially run
on the track and have it timed?

1501
01:41:34.699 --> 01:41:36.297
That's what I'm saying, Burt.

1502
01:41:38.994 --> 01:41:41.292
You'll never know what
this means to me, Otto.

1503
01:41:41.392 --> 01:41:44.389
25 years I've lived for this day,
25 years.

1504
01:41:44.689 --> 01:41:48.385
Sometimes you've got to bend the rules
a little, today's one of those days.

1505
01:41:48.885 --> 01:41:51.981
- Thank you from the bottom of my heart.
- Thank you.

1506
01:41:57.876 --> 01:42:00.573
- What did they say?
- What happened?

1507
01:42:02.271 --> 01:42:03.969
They said I could run.

1508
01:42:04.869 --> 01:42:06.067
That's great!

1509
01:42:06.667 --> 01:42:09.064
- So why the long face then?
- Well, I don't know...

1510
01:42:09.164 --> 01:42:12.561
it's just starting to sink in
and I've got a problem a big problem.

1511
01:42:12.761 --> 01:42:16.157
As soon as I go over a hundred and
ten it starts to wobble like heck...

1512
01:42:16.257 --> 01:42:17.755
a bad speed wobble.

1513
01:42:17.756 --> 01:42:21.252
Well, it did look like you were
about as stable as my last wife.

1514
01:42:22.950 --> 01:42:25.548
I've got a theory
and I think I'm right.

1515
01:42:25.648 --> 01:42:28.445
I need about twenty car batteries.

1516
01:42:28.545 --> 01:42:29.444
Twenty?

1517
01:42:30.343 --> 01:42:32.441
Is it ok to steel
these batteries, Burt?

1518
01:42:32.741 --> 01:42:34.539
We're not steeling them Marty,
we're souveniring them.

1519
01:42:34.639 --> 01:42:36.437
Careful of that acid there.

1520
01:42:36.837 --> 01:42:38.435
What do we do
with them now?

1521
01:42:38.635 --> 01:42:41.332
Well, we're going to talk someone
into lending us a painter's blow torch.

1522
01:42:41.632 --> 01:42:43.030
A painter's blow torch?

1523
01:42:45.428 --> 01:42:47.925
What are we going to do
with all this metal, Burt?

1524
01:42:48.425 --> 01:42:53.420
Well, when this cools down,
we'll have ourselves a lead brick.

1525
01:42:53.720 --> 01:42:57.516
- What do you do with a lead brick?
- Place it in the front of the motorcycle.

1526
01:42:58.215 --> 01:43:00.313
- And that's your plan?
- Yeah.

1527
01:43:01.412 --> 01:43:05.907
Well, you must get the centre
of pressure behind the centre of gravity...

1528
01:43:06.007 --> 01:43:09.004
and if you don't get it right
then she'll start to fish tail...

1529
01:43:09.005 --> 01:43:12.001
- when you get her wound up.
- What do you mean by fish tail?

1530
01:43:12.201 --> 01:43:15.148
Well, like a fish's behind you know.
It'll start doing that.

1531
01:43:15.149 --> 01:43:18.095
And that's what happened today
when I had the handling run.

1532
01:43:18.295 --> 01:43:21.991
And so in a panic I lifted my head up
from behind the screen...

1533
01:43:22.291 --> 01:43:25.987
and suddenly the bike started
to go straight and...

1534
01:43:26.287 --> 01:43:30.583
I knew I'd solved the problem somehow
by sticking my head up into the wind.

1535
01:43:31.682 --> 01:43:33.180
- I don't get it.
- Me neither.

1536
01:43:33.480 --> 01:43:35.578
Well, I'll show you.
Let me have that.

1537
01:43:36.777 --> 01:43:38.475
What are you doing?

1538
01:43:38.675 --> 01:43:42.271
Imagine the cigar
is my streamliner.

1539
01:43:42.371 --> 01:43:43.969
Don't poke holes in the cigar.

1540
01:43:44.269 --> 01:43:47.366
Now if I hold it in the middle
and blow on it. Like so.

1541
01:43:49.164 --> 01:43:50.962
See how unstable it is?

1542
01:43:51.162 --> 01:43:52.461
Now if I...

1543
01:43:53.760 --> 01:43:55.458
- shift the...
- Not again!

1544
01:43:55.758 --> 01:43:58.255
Centre of pressure here.
And blow on it.

1545
01:44:03.150 --> 01:44:04.649
See it's much more stable.

1546
01:44:04.848 --> 01:44:09.044
Just the centre of pressure
is behind the centre of gravity...

1547
01:44:09.344 --> 01:44:12.141
and that's what I'm trying to fix
with the lead brick you see.

1548
01:44:12.341 --> 01:44:13.939
You're quite clever,
did you know that, Burt?

1549
01:44:14.239 --> 01:44:17.736
Now all I need to do is to test
my theory before I run on the salt...

1550
01:44:17.935 --> 01:44:18.833
and I was thinking of,
you know...

1551
01:44:18.834 --> 01:44:22.431
crossing over the state line
from here in Utah to Nevada...

1552
01:44:22.631 --> 01:44:26.727
where there's no speed limit and running
with a lead brick in the front of it.

1553
01:45:16.976 --> 01:45:18.475
- Good morning.
- Morning.

1554
01:45:18.874 --> 01:45:20.872
Do you know how fast you were
going back there?

1555
01:45:20.972 --> 01:45:22.271
Yeah, about...

1556
01:45:22.770 --> 01:45:25.168
150, 160 miles an hour.

1557
01:45:28.065 --> 01:45:30.163
Yeah, that sounds about right.

1558
01:45:31.162 --> 01:45:32.860
How's he going to talk
his way out of this one?

1559
01:45:33.759 --> 01:45:36.856
He sure got his arse
in a sling this time, don't he?

1560
01:45:37.156 --> 01:45:40.852
So what's the situation with this thing?
You don't have any license plates on it.

1561
01:45:41.052 --> 01:45:44.349
- It's registered in New Zealand.
- New Zealand?

1562
01:45:44.449 --> 01:45:46.746
Yeah, that's where I come from.

1563
01:45:50.043 --> 01:45:51.740
Alright, you mean to tell me...

1564
01:45:51.741 --> 01:45:54.439
that this contraption of yours
is registered for the road?

1565
01:45:55.538 --> 01:45:58.734
- Yeah, in New Zealand.
- New Zealand, right.

1566
01:45:59.234 --> 01:46:02.531
Well, how about taking it easy
here in Nevada?

1567
01:46:02.830 --> 01:46:04.827
Just because we don't have
a speed limit don't mean...

1568
01:46:04.828 --> 01:46:08.325
- we want people killing themselves.
- No, sounds fair enough to me.

1569
01:46:09.224 --> 01:46:12.221
- Right, you have a good day then.
- I will, thank you.

1570
01:46:12.222 --> 01:46:13.520
Burt, everything OK?

1571
01:46:15.218 --> 01:46:19.014
Well, fellows, we're going to have
to give the lead brick...

1572
01:46:19.114 --> 01:46:21.112
the old Spanish archer.

1573
01:46:21.412 --> 01:46:24.409
- Spanish archer?
- Yeah, the big elbow, you know.

1574
01:46:25.308 --> 01:46:27.206
The lead brick has got to go.

1575
01:46:27.506 --> 01:46:29.803
Who's stupid idea was that anyway?

1576
01:46:30.003 --> 01:46:30.802
It was yours.

1577
01:46:30.902 --> 01:46:35.697
Yeah. Well, I'm just going to have
to ride her, the way she is.

1578
01:46:36.097 --> 01:46:37.396
What about that speed wobble?

1579
01:46:37.695 --> 01:46:40.992
Well, I'll cross that bridge
when I get there.

1580
01:46:41.392 --> 01:46:43.889
- I've got another problem too.
- Yeah, what now?

1581
01:46:44.189 --> 01:46:46.686
Well, when I get her going...

1582
01:46:46.886 --> 01:46:50.583
there's an enormous amount of heat
comes off the exhaust pipe...

1583
01:46:50.882 --> 01:46:54.179
and I hope
it doesn't cook my leg.

1584
01:46:54.978 --> 01:46:59.174
Maybe you can wrap some asbestos cloth
around it, that should fix it right.

1585
01:46:59.175 --> 01:47:00.473
That's a good idea.

1586
01:47:01.072 --> 01:47:03.570
So you got any more problems
you want to tell us about?

1587
01:47:03.570 --> 01:47:05.667
Yes, yes, my old ticker.

1588
01:47:06.467 --> 01:47:08.964
- You've got a bad heart?
- Yes, I have.

1589
01:47:12.960 --> 01:47:14.958
I've got a little surprise
for you.

1590
01:47:15.458 --> 01:47:18.255
- What?
- Close your eyes and give me your hand.

1591
01:47:18.455 --> 01:47:20.952
- What?
- Just close your eyes. Come on.

1592
01:47:21.252 --> 01:47:23.749
- What for?
- Because I said so, mister, come on.

1593
01:47:26.547 --> 01:47:27.945
Keep walking.

1594
01:47:28.045 --> 01:47:31.641
Wendy, you're not going to make
a fool of an old man I hope.

1595
01:47:31.741 --> 01:47:33.340
I'd never do that, Burt.

1596
01:47:33.540 --> 01:47:34.638
Never.

1597
01:47:34.938 --> 01:47:36.337
Never. Okay. Okay.

1598
01:47:36.636 --> 01:47:38.135
Now turn around.

1599
01:47:38.734 --> 01:47:40.032
Alright.

1600
01:47:40.033 --> 01:47:41.931
Now, hold your hands out.

1601
01:47:42.531 --> 01:47:44.129
Put that in your pocket.

1602
01:47:44.229 --> 01:47:45.328
Alright.

1603
01:47:45.528 --> 01:47:46.626
There we go good.

1604
01:47:47.925 --> 01:47:49.424
You can open them.

1605
01:48:04.509 --> 01:48:06.307
What are you all staring at?

1606
01:48:08.105 --> 01:48:10.103
- What is this?
- Burt...

1607
01:48:10.303 --> 01:48:14.099
we've unanimously voted you here on
the Salt planes, sportsman of the year...

1608
01:48:14.299 --> 01:48:17.695
because we figured nobody has
ever travelled as far as you have...

1609
01:48:17.696 --> 01:48:18.994
to be here for speed week...

1610
01:48:19.094 --> 01:48:22.790
so normally we would present
a trophy or something like that...

1611
01:48:23.090 --> 01:48:25.987
but considering your case
we thought a few extra dollars...

1612
01:48:25.988 --> 01:48:28.884
would be more appreciated
so we past the hat around.

1613
01:48:32.680 --> 01:48:33.979
My goodness!

1614
01:48:36.976 --> 01:48:38.674
There are no words.

1615
01:48:52.361 --> 01:48:53.959
Well, thank you all.

1616
01:48:54.758 --> 01:48:56.856
Thank you all very much.

1617
01:48:58.554 --> 01:49:00.952
I'm sorry,
I don't know what to say.

1618
01:49:02.550 --> 01:49:05.448
Oh dear, it's quite
overwhelming you know...

1619
01:49:05.747 --> 01:49:08.245
it's 25 years dream
to come here.

1620
01:49:11.242 --> 01:49:16.137
I should try
to justify you, your respect and...

1621
01:49:17.236 --> 01:49:22.131
you know the original speed
of my old bike was 54 miles an hour.

1622
01:49:25.128 --> 01:49:29.424
And today I'm hoping to,
you know, improve it a little.

1623
01:49:39.613 --> 01:49:42.910
<i>The cars are at the start line now.
The next one is the 86...</i>

1624
01:49:43.210 --> 01:49:46.606
<i>On the bucket seat
the pilot is ready to be pushed out.</i>

1625
01:49:56.297 --> 01:49:57.995
<i>Next competitor is Burt Munro.</i>

1626
01:49:58.794 --> 01:50:01.791
<i>All the way from Invercargill,
New Zealand.</i>

1627
01:50:02.990 --> 01:50:06.287
<i>Burt Munro's entry
was approved just yesterday.</i>

1628
01:50:14.678 --> 01:50:16.277
Burt, where'd you get this stuff?

1629
01:50:16.377 --> 01:50:18.474
- What?
- I say, where'd you get this stuff?

1630
01:50:18.774 --> 01:50:22.570
I tore an old electric blanket apart
and got the asbestos cloth out of it.

1631
01:50:23.070 --> 01:50:25.167
You got those heart pills?

1632
01:50:25.168 --> 01:50:27.465
- Are you okay?
- Better take one, yeah.

1633
01:50:27.765 --> 01:50:29.314
They're almost ready.

1634
01:50:29.315 --> 01:50:30.862
Guys, come on, let's go.

1635
01:50:31.961 --> 01:50:34.359
You know the bottle says
that they may cause drowsiness...

1636
01:50:34.359 --> 01:50:36.756
- do not operate machinery.
- I know that.

1637
01:50:37.356 --> 01:50:39.154
Well, you're not supposed
to take two of them anyway.

1638
01:50:39.453 --> 01:50:41.551
One for me
and one for the old girl.

1639
01:50:41.851 --> 01:50:43.350
Nitro-glycerine.

1640
01:50:43.549 --> 01:50:45.048
Should make it go faster.

1641
01:50:45.647 --> 01:50:47.146
Have some of this, love.

1642
01:50:51.142 --> 01:50:52.341
There you go.

1643
01:50:58.834 --> 01:51:01.431
- Yeah, we're almost there.
- Alright, here we go.

1644
01:51:02.131 --> 01:51:03.529
- Hold her still.
- Your goggles.

1645
01:51:03.629 --> 01:51:04.528
- What?
- Goggles.

1646
01:51:04.628 --> 01:51:06.926
- Put your goggles on.
- I know, calm down.

1647
01:51:10.722 --> 01:51:15.417
I can't get my leg in because
of the asbestos cloth on it.

1648
01:51:23.509 --> 01:51:24.808
Let me take it off.

1649
01:51:25.108 --> 01:51:28.704
- What about your leg in that heat?
- Screw it, I've got a spare one.

1650
01:51:30.802 --> 01:51:32.400
Right, Burt.

1651
01:51:32.600 --> 01:51:33.999
Get those goggles.

1652
01:51:35.098 --> 01:51:37.495
- Ready?
- Alright, you know the way.

1653
01:51:37.795 --> 01:51:38.694
Make sure you come back.

1654
01:51:38.894 --> 01:51:40.093
Come on, let's go!

1655
01:51:40.392 --> 01:51:41.591
Right, push!

1656
01:51:42.590 --> 01:51:44.388
Come on, fellas. Push faster!

1657
01:51:46.486 --> 01:51:47.685
Keep running.

1658
01:51:51.182 --> 01:51:52.980
Keep it straight, buddy.

1659
01:51:54.678 --> 01:51:56.876
Bring it in, Burt. Come on.
Go, go, go...

1660
01:51:57.276 --> 01:51:58.474
Let's go, Burt!

1661
01:52:04.269 --> 01:52:05.168
Come on, Burt!

1662
01:52:05.867 --> 01:52:07.465
You can do it, Burt.

1663
01:52:07.765 --> 01:52:09.963
He's got no parachute,
he's got no brakes.

1664
01:52:29.443 --> 01:52:31.341
158.647.

1665
01:52:31.841 --> 01:52:35.238
Mile one,
158.647 miles per hour.

1666
01:52:35.437 --> 01:52:36.736
Go, Burt!

1667
01:52:37.036 --> 01:52:38.834
- Go on!
- Go, Burt!

1668
01:52:39.333 --> 01:52:41.431
- Make us proud, honey!
- Burt!

1669
01:52:56.416 --> 01:52:58.414
167.921.

1670
01:52:58.614 --> 01:53:02.211
Mile two,
167.921 miles per hour.

1671
01:53:02.410 --> 01:53:05.008
Break it, Burt.
Come on! Go, go, go!

1672
01:53:05.108 --> 01:53:06.107
Come on, Burt.

1673
01:53:16.197 --> 01:53:20.093
<i>Mile three,
171.371 miles per hour.</i>

1674
01:53:20.292 --> 01:53:21.791
Come on, come on, come on!

1675
01:53:33.379 --> 01:53:36.676
Mile four,
172.485 miles per hour.

1676
01:53:37.475 --> 01:53:38.374
Yeah!

1677
01:53:38.674 --> 01:53:39.573
Come on!

1678
01:53:41.172 --> 01:53:44.069
<i>Mile five,
183.694 miles per hour.</i>

1679
01:54:04.049 --> 01:54:05.947
<i>193.728.</i>

1680
01:54:06.246 --> 01:54:09.044
Mile six,
193.728 miles per hour.

1681
01:54:10.143 --> 01:54:12.141
Come on, come on!

1682
01:54:17.136 --> 01:54:19.433
Come on, Burt.
You can do it!

1683
01:54:19.633 --> 01:54:20.732
Come on, Burt!

1684
01:54:21.231 --> 01:54:24.728
<i>Mile seven,
194.211 miles per hour.</i>

1685
01:54:25.327 --> 01:54:27.825
- Go, Burt!
- Burt, go!

1686
01:55:12.580 --> 01:55:13.379
What is it?

1687
01:55:14.378 --> 01:55:16.376
201.851.

1688
01:55:16.776 --> 01:55:21.371
Mile eight,
201.851 miles per hour.

1689
01:55:29.064 --> 01:55:31.661
Ladies and gentlemen,
that's a new record...

1690
01:55:31.861 --> 01:55:35.957
201.851 miles per hour.

1691
01:55:38.454 --> 01:55:40.552
Burt, I hope you're going
to stop soon.

1692
01:55:40.952 --> 01:55:43.749
- He's gone back!
- Back where?

1693
01:55:44.049 --> 01:55:48.045
Back to whatever planet he came from
because he sure ain't from this one.

1694
01:56:42.090 --> 01:56:43.989
I really did toast my leg.

1695
01:56:49.683 --> 01:56:50.882
I did it.

1696
01:56:51.681 --> 01:56:52.780
I did it.

1697
01:57:22.850 --> 01:57:25.547
Tom, can you get that,
my hands are wet.

1698
01:57:30.942 --> 01:57:32.139
Hello?

1699
01:57:32.140 --> 01:57:35.837
<i>This is the United States calling I have
a collect call from Mr. Burt Munro...</i>

1700
01:57:36.036 --> 01:57:37.335
<i>will you accept the charge?</i>

1701
01:57:37.435 --> 01:57:41.731
- Mum, it's Burt calling collect.
- It is? Accept the call, accept the call!

1702
01:57:42.030 --> 01:57:43.329
My mum said we can accept the call.

1703
01:57:43.429 --> 01:57:46.226
<i>- Go ahead, sir.
- Hello Tom, is that you?</i>

1704
01:57:46.426 --> 01:57:48.524
<i>- Yes.
- It's me, Burt.</i>

1705
01:57:48.724 --> 01:57:52.220
<i>I did it Tom,
she's the world's fastest Indian.</i>

1706
01:57:52.320 --> 01:57:53.219
She is?

1707
01:57:53.519 --> 01:57:54.718
Dad, dad!

1708
01:57:55.317 --> 01:57:58.214
Dad! He did it! Burt did it!

1709
01:57:58.514 --> 01:57:59.913
He set a new record.

1710
01:58:18.594 --> 01:58:19.593
How is it going?

1711
01:58:19.693 --> 01:58:21.091
Hello, mate!

1712
01:58:21.191 --> 01:58:22.590
- Hey, Duncan.
- Congratulations, Burt.

1713
01:58:22.591 --> 01:58:23.988
Hello, Frank.
How are you?

1714
01:58:24.188 --> 01:58:26.186
- Welcome home, Burt.
- Hello, George.

1715
01:58:26.286 --> 01:58:29.583
My goodness, you've made
this place look spiffing, mate.

1716
01:58:29.883 --> 01:58:31.080
You did us proud.

1717
01:58:31.081 --> 01:58:34.578
- You put Invercargill on the map.
- Well, I reckon so, yeah.

1718
01:58:34.678 --> 01:58:37.375
- What have you got planned now?
- Right now I've a lot of work to do...

1719
01:58:37.475 --> 01:58:40.272
if I'm to get back to Bonneville
next year, you know.

1720
01:58:40.372 --> 01:58:42.570
So, more early mornings then?

1721
01:58:42.670 --> 01:58:44.568
Yeah, more early mornings.

1722
01:58:44.768 --> 01:58:45.965
Hello, love.

1723
01:58:45.966 --> 01:58:48.264
- Welcome home.
- Nice to be back.

1724
01:58:49.463 --> 01:58:51.361
- Hello, Tom.
- Hey, Burt.

1725
01:58:51.661 --> 01:58:53.259
How are you, son?

1726
01:58:53.659 --> 01:58:54.957
Good to see ya.

1727
01:58:55.257 --> 01:58:56.856
You're growing up a bit, huh?

1728
01:58:57.455 --> 01:58:59.453
I looked after your lemon tree
just like you told me.

1729
01:58:59.553 --> 01:59:00.852
You did, yeah.

1730
01:59:01.051 --> 01:59:02.350
Looking good, too.

1731
01:59:02.850 --> 01:59:04.048
Yeah, it's beautiful.

1732
01:59:05.347 --> 01:59:07.345
- I fed the chickens.
- You did?

1733
01:59:07.545 --> 01:59:09.443
- And mum cooked all the eggs.
- Oh, yeah...

1734
01:59:09.743 --> 01:59:11.741
- did they taste good?
- Yep.

1735
01:59:11.940 --> 01:59:13.839
- Yeah, good. Have you got my key?
- Here it is.

1736
01:59:13.839 --> 01:59:15.237
- Right thanks.
- I took good care of it.

1737
01:59:15.637 --> 01:59:18.134
- I knew you would.
- How fast did you go?

1738
01:59:18.334 --> 01:59:21.631
Mighty fast. In one of my runs
I did over 200 miles an hour.

1739
01:59:21.930 --> 01:59:24.828
What would happen if you opened
your mouth at that speed?

1740
01:59:25.127 --> 01:59:27.425
Well, you'd blow the backside
out of your pants I reckon.

1741
01:59:29.623 --> 01:59:30.822
Right, let's see.

1742
01:59:33.419 --> 01:59:36.316
Nice to be home.
Back in my shed.

